<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-26 15:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mubarak, Arafat Meet on Tuesday, Says Egyptian FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 26 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National Authority
President Yasser Arafat will meet with Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak on Tuesday on the outcome of his recent visit to
Washington, said Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Moussa told reporters that he himself will have talks with
Arafat prior to the two leaders' meeting upon the latter's arrival
here Monday night.
</P>
<P>
"Arafat will brief Mubarak on the outcome of his recent trip to
Washington and meeting with U.S. President Bill Clinton and the
Palestinian stand towards the development in the peace process in
the light of these talks," he said.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister said other Arab talks will be held after
Arafat's visit to Cairo, the second one in a week.
</P>
<P>
King Hussein of Jordan made a surprise visit to Cairo Sunday
for talks with Mubarak on pushing forward the peace process, which
a senior Egyptian official said marked the commencement of a
series of Arab consultations.
</P>
<P>
Following his talks in the U.S., the Palestinian leader started
a Maghreb tour during which he visited Mauritania, Morocco,
Algeria and Tunisia.
</P>
<P>
On the way, Arafat has been voicing his frustration with the
Washington talks which he described as a "failure" and urging
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu to fulfill his
obligations.
</P>
<P>
Arafat, during a stop in Algiers Sunday, called for holding an
emergency Arab summit to look into the latest developments in the
Arab world, with particular focus on the Palestinian cause.
</P>
<P>
To drum up European support for the peace process, Arafat is
now in London for talks with British Prime Minister Tony Blair
whose country holds the six-month rotating chairmanship of the
European Union.
</P>
<P>
Arafat is being accompanied by PLO Executive Committee
Secretary Mahmoud Abbas (Abu Mazen), Planning and International
Cooperation Minister Nabil Shaath and Arafat's Information Adviser
Nabil Abu Rydainah.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peace talks have deadlocked since last
March when Israel started to build a new settlement in Arab East
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The recent talks Clinton held in Washington with Arafat and
Netanyahu have failed to break the ice. 
</P>
</TEXT>
