<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Investigators to Question Clinton's Aides </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 26 (Xinhua) -- Whitewater investigators are
preparing to question aides and friends of President Bill Clinton
before a federal grand jury about allegations that Clinton had an
affair with a former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile a White House aide said, "We're working this out
almost hour by hour."
</P>
<P>
"Nobody wants to get the facts out more quickly and more
publicly than Bill Clinton," White House communications director
Ann Lewis said on NBC's "Today" show. "We have to do this in a way
that is appropriate."
</P>
<P>
Whitewater prosecutor Kenneth Starr spent much of Sunday at his
office amid a report by ABC News that an eyewitness saw Clinton
and former White House intern Monica Lewinsky in an intimate
encounter in the spring of 1996, just before Lewinsky was
transferred to the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, former White House chief of staff Leon Panetta
and former deputy chief of staff Evelyn Lieberman denied that
either had been notified by any White House aide or Secret Service
agent who might have witnessed "certain sexual activities between
the president and Monica Lewinsky."
</P>
<P>
Lewinsky's lawyer William Ginsburg pressed, meanwhile, for an
immunity deal for his client, pledging to "remain in Washington as
long as it takes to see that the truth in every detail, wherever
it may fall, comes out."
</P>
<P>
On shows on NBC, CBS and ABC Sunday, Ginsburg said he has
talked to investigators about what Lewinsky, 24, will tell them in
exchange for immunity from prosecution.
</P>
<P>
Clinton last week denied having any "improper sexual
relationship" with the young woman or that he asked her to lie to
investigators.
</P>
<P>
Lewinsky filed a sworn affidavit in the Paula Jones sexual
harassment case denying an affair with Clinton -- an assertion
that is contradicted by secretly taped conversations now in the
hands of Whitewater prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
On ABC, Ginsburg said he had made "a couple of oral attorney
proffers" to Whitewater prosecutors. A proffer is an outline --
ordinarily in writing -- of what evidence a potential cooperating
witness in an investigation will provide investigators.
</P>
<P>
A source familiar with the matter reportedly said Lewinsky
is willing to tell prosecutors that she had sex with the
president.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's longtime friend Vernon Jordan is among those facing
grand jury appearances as early as Tuesday in the investigation.
Lieberman is also expected to be subpoenaed as well.
</P>
<P>
White House political consultant Paul Begala criticized Starr
for "firing off subpoenas like an Uzi" submachine gun.
</P>
<P>
Clinton talked through the weekend with heavyweight advisers,
including former Commerce Secretary Mickey Kantor.
</P>
<P>
Polls found many Americans deeply concerned about whether
Clinton had an affair with the then-21-year-old Lewinsky and
whether he encouraged her in recent months to lie about it.
</P>
<P>
Polls by the Los Angeles Times, USA Today, CBS News-New York
Times, ABC News, Newsweek and NBC News-Wall Street Journal found
that many Americans regard the allegations involving Clinton and
Lewinsky -- if proven -- as grounds for his departure from office.
</P>
<P>
The president and first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton tried to
maintain an air of normalcy Sunday, attending religious services
as usual. Clinton rehearsed his Tuesday night State of the Union
speech before watching the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
Henry Hyde, chairman of the Judiciary Committee of the House of
Representatives, spoke cautiously about the possibility of an
impeachment inquiry should Clinton be found to have encouraged
Lewinsky to commit perjury. "Nothing much will happen until the
Democrats decide something should happen," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
