<DOCNO> XIE19980127.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Technology Key to Progress: Zimbabwe's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 26 (Xinhua) -- A Zimbabwean educationist said
Monday there is need for developing countries to embrace modern
technology so as to produce goods at low costs and compete on the
international market.
</P>
<P>
''Industrialized countries are able to produce at low costs
because they use computers and modern technology in
manufacturing. It is imperative for developing countries to
embrace technology and produce at low cost so as to compete in
international markets,'' Vice-Chancellor of the National
University of Science and Technology (NUST) of Zimbabwe Phineas
Makhurane said.
</P>
<P>
He was addressing a Commonwealth in-country training program
on information technology for manufacturing held in Bulawayo, the
country's second largest city by the NUST's Department of
Computer Science in collaboration with the U.S.-based University
of Warwick's manufacturing group.
</P>
<P>
He also said NUST graduates could influence the introduction
of technology-oriented entrepreneurships in the informal sector.
</P>
<P>
''Our aim is to produce a graduate who is not a stranger to
the non-formal sector. It's that sector that will eventually make
the difference as the country's industrial base may actually
begin to shrink because we pay too much lip service to attracting
foreign investment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, President of the Confederation of Zimbabwe
Industries Jonee Blanchfield said there was need to close the gap
between the education and industrial sectors.
</P>
<P>
She said that students from universities should be attached to
industry so that they will have an inside knowledge to what
happens there.
</P>
<P>
''Otherwise there is a crisis of expectations from both the
employer's and the graduate's point of view. If industry could
sponsor specific students, that would make it even more
sensible,'' she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
