<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kazakhstan Sees A Bright Future of Baikonur Cosmodrome </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA-ATA, January 26 (Xinhua) -- Tohtab Aubakirov, the defense
and space industry adviser to the president of Kazakhstan, said
here Monday that the Baikonur Cosmodrome which is leased by Russia
has a great scientific potential and a bright future for further
development.
</P>
<P>
He made the remark at a press conference where he briefed
reporters on the plan to launch the "Union TM-27" spacecraft,
which will send Kazak astronaut T. Musabayev on January 29 to the
Russian Space Station "MIR" to do scientific research for 104 days.
</P>
<P>
Aubakirov said the Kazak astronaut will do research in the
fields of geography, agriculture, geomorphology, physics,
chemistry, space biology and medicine.
</P>
<P>
Vladimir Shkolnik, president of the Ministry of Science, told
the press that rumors of the elimination of Baikonur Cosmodrome
were groundless. He said lots of international space projects will
take place in Baikonur Cosmodrome. Kazakhstan and Russia will
jointly work to make the space center succeed and to lift the
facility out from under the temporary problems of finance,
environment and tariffs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980127.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Companies Optimistic About Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 26 (Xinhua) -- South African captains of
industry and commerce are confident in the country's political
future and they predicted a growth rate of 2.6 percent this year,
according to a survey released here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The figure, according to the survey of executives of the top
100 industrial companies on the Johannesburg Stock Exchange, is
nearly one percentage point more than the 1.7 percent growth
estimated for 1997.
</P>
<P>
The survey, conducted by the Market Research Bureau of the
University of South Africa, also foresee an inflation rate of 8.1
percent, which is about the same level as last year.
</P>
<P>
The prime overdraft rate is expected to decrease to 18 percent
by December 1998 and there would be an improvement in South
Africa's balance of payments account and in net gold and other
foreign reserves, South African Press Association quoted the
report as saying.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investment in the country was also expected to go up
this year in response to the business and socio-political
optimism, the report said.
</P>
<P>
However, the report warned of a potential damage to the
economy due to the combined impact of the El Nino phenomenon, the
international banking crisis and the depreciation of South
African currency Rand, to the U.S. Dollar.
</P>
<P>
The foreign exchange rate could rise to an average 5.03 Rand
against the Dollar, up from the current level of about 4.9.
</P>
<P>
"The time has come for politicians and economists to put their
heads together and devise means of curbing the wild swings that
are fast becoming a feature of financial markets, and of
insulating the world economy from damaging consequences," the
report said.
</P>
<P>
Despite the positive pointers to a bullish economy, 92 percent
of the interviewed believed that the government was behind set
targets in its macro-economic strategy of Growth, Employment and
Redistribution (GEAR).
</P>
<P>
"More than three quarters of the executives are of the view
that the basic conditions of employment bill will have a
detrimental effect on employment," the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
