<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, January 26 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- The United States and France Monday reaffirmed
their commitment to the security and stability in Kuwait,
official Kuwait News Agency (Kuna) reported.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait's first Deputy Prime Minister and Foreign Minister
Sheikh Sabah Al-Ahmad Al-Jaber Al-Sabah received a letter from
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, in which she renewed
the U.S. firm commitment to Kuwait's security and praised
bilateral relations, according to Kuna.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait signed defense treaties with the U.S. and France
following the 1991 Gulf War which helped to drive the Iraqi
occupation troops out from the small Gulf emirate.
(Kuwait-US-France)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- British aircraft carrier HMS Invincible and a
supply ship have entered the Gulf waters to reinforce possible
allied operations against Iraq, the Bahraini News Agency monitored
here reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
"The carrier will carry out training exercises with allied
forces in the region," the agency quoted Caroline Alcock,
spokeswoman for the British Embassy in Bahrain, as saying.
</P>
<P>
The British carrier arrived in the Gulf amid mounting tensions
between Iraq and the U.N. on arms inspection. (Britain-Iraq-Carrier)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin Monday approved a
12-task program that calls for economic reforms, Russia's
accession to the World Trade Organization and more contacts with
the European Union.
</P>
<P>
The program calls for land reform, reduced taxes and an end to
wage arrears, increased investment and stronger legal safeguards
for both citizens and companies.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin said the new program would introduce more personal
responsibility for his ministers. (Russia-Government Program)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MANILA -- A total of 93 persons have been arrested by the
Philippine police in the last two weeks for violation of the gun
ban, a senior official from the Commission on Elections (Comelec)
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Bernardo Pardo, Chairman of the Comelec, revealed this
development during a coordinating conference held by the Comelec
and the Philippine National Police.
</P>
<P>
The Comelec has imposed the gun ban since January 11, the
beginning day for the registration of candidates, to ensure the
May general elections proceed smoothly. (Philippines-Gun Ban)
</P>
</TEXT>
