<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Calm Returns to Harare After Looting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 26 (Xinhua) -- There was relative calm in
Harare Monday despite wide spread rumors that the city was again
expected to brought to another halt following last week's
devastating food riots.
</P>
<P>
A survey around the city revealed its business became usual in
most areas. Flea markets were bustling with activity and all
supermarkets were open.
</P>
<P>
Rumors spread like veld fire over the weekend with commuter
operators suspected of spreading a message that people should
stay away from work on Monday to force the government into
reducing the prices for most basic commodities.
</P>
<P>
The prices of basic goods were increased by an average 20
percent at the beginning of this year, with the private sector
attributing the increases to the devaluation of the Zimbabwean
Dollar and high interest and inflation rates.
</P>
<P>
The soaring prices triggered the three-day food riots which
started Monday in Harare and the dormitory town of Chitungwiza
before spreading to other cities like Chegutu and Mutare.
</P>
<P>
A statement released by the police Sunday said people should
ignore the message and go to work as usual.
</P>
<P>
There was a normal flow of traffic going in and out of the
city center, dispelling fears that commuter operators might be
forced by sources of the rumors to stay away to get off the
roads.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, heavily armed Zimbabwe national army soldiers
maintained their heavy presence at most points leading into the
city center in a bid to flush out any suspected looters from
gaining entrance into the city.
</P>
<P>
The police, together with the soldiers, had so far recovered
millions worth of goods looted during the riots in the high
density areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
