<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Leone Junta Soldiers Urged to Give Up to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 26 (Xinhua) -- An officer of the West African
Peace-keeping Force (ECOMOG) Monday called on soldiers of Sierra
Leone's military junta to surrender, just three months for the
planned hand-over of the military regime.
</P>
<P>
Several hundred soldiers have done so and the surrenders have
been influential among the junta forces, the British Broadcasting
Corporation reported.
</P>
<P>
Since December last year, 300 Sierra Leonean army personnel,
150 police officers, including some from the special security
division and over 400 former rebel fighters have voluntarily
surrendered to ECOMOG.
</P>
<P>
Some of them went to the sub-regional force with arms, the
report quoted an ECOMOG Colonel as saying.
</P>
<P>
Among those who surrendered are two of the top leaders of the
former rebel group Revolutionary United Front, which had fought
successive governments of the country since early 1990s until it
allied to the junta immediately after the coup last May.
</P>
<P>
However, the names of the surrendered army-menr and police
officers, as well as some eminent civilians, were not disclosed
for security reasons and the safety of their relatives in town,
the officer said.
</P>
<P>
The Colonel called on the junta army to lay down their
weapons, saying that "their future is very bright."
</P>
<P>
Under a peace accord on the crisis in Sierra Leone, combatants
in the country should be disarmed in December last year and the
junta hand over power to the ousted civilian government led by
President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah in April this year.
</P>
<P>
But junta leader Johnny Paul Koroma later dismissed the
deadline as unrealistic due to ECOMOG's inability to start the
disarmament exercise and the delay of international relief goods.
</P>
<P>
Despite the change in the junta's stance, both the United
States and west African countries have insisted that the Koroma
regime follow the peace accord strictly.
</P>
<P>
A U.N. fact-finding team paid a three-day visit to Freetown
two weeks ago to pave way for the deployment of U.N. military
observers in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Member nations of the Economic Community of West African
States (ECOWAS) are consulting to search for modalities to
resolve the crisis.
</P>
<P>
The ECOMOG officer said the multi-national force will follow
whatever decision taken by the U.N. and ECOWAS to restore
constitutional order in Sierra Leone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
