<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Govt Outlaws LTTE </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, January 26 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan government has
outlawed the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE), the official
TV station Rupavahini said in a special statement Monday night.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the Sri Lankan government decided to ban the
LTTE with immediate effect.
</P>
<P>
But the TV statement did not elaborate. Government officials
were not available for comment.
</P>
<P>
The decision came one day after a powerful truck bomb exploded
in Kandy, the ancient Sri Lankan capital 115 km east of Colombo,
killing 12 people and damaging the holiest place of worship of Sri
Lankan Buddhists, the Tooth Relic Temple, Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
Three LTTE suicide attackers were also among the dead.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE has been fighting government troops in a bid to create
a separate state of their own in the north and east of the island
nation.
</P>
<P>
The decision is seen as a crucial step and it might suggest the
government is going to toughen its stance towards the LTTE,
political observers here said.
</P>
<P>
Although several countries, including India and the United
States, have already banned the LTTE before, the Sri Lankan
government had stopped short of taking the step until Monday,
leaving the door open for the LTTE to hold talks with it.
</P>
</TEXT>
