<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO Reinforces Chagas Disease, Leprosy Elimination </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, January 26 (Xinhua) -- The Executive Board of the World
Health Organization (WHO) today called for continuous
international efforts to eliminate Chagas disease by 2010 and
leprosy by 2000.
</P>
<P>
In two resolutions to be submitted for adoption by the World
Health Assembly in May, the WHO executive board outlined what it
felt should be the major thrusts of action against these two
public health threats.
</P>
<P>
Chagas disease exists only on the American continent and has
already affected 16 to 18 million people, while some 100 million,
or 25 percent of the population of Latin America, are at risk of
acquiring the disease, according to WHO statistics.
</P>
<P>
The disease is caused by a parasite, Trypanosoma cruzi,
transmitted to humans by triatomine bugs and it extends from
Mexico to Argentina.
</P>
<P>
While expressing its satisfaction with the progress made by
member states in eliminating the transmission of Chagas disease,
the executive board called on WHO and its director-general to
support ongoing efforts to eliminate transmission by 2010.
</P>
<P>
As for leprosy, the World Health Assembly in May 1991 set a
target of prevalence at below one case per 10,000 population as a
gauge for the global elimination of leprosy as a public health
problem by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Since 1990, the global prevalence of leprosy has been reduced
by 76 percent due to program coverage and implementation of
multidrug therapy throughout the world, WHO said.
</P>
<P>
The number of endemic countries has been reduced from 122 in
1985 to 55 at the beginning of 1997, while the cumulative number
of individuals cured had reached 8.4 million by the beginning of
1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
