<HEADLINE> People's Daily Editorial Marks Jiang's Speech on Taiwan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 26 (Xinhua) -- The Tuesday edition of the
People's Daily, China's leading newspaper, will carry an editorial
stressing political negotiations constitute a key to promoting the
relations across the Taiwan Straits.
</P>
<P>
On January 30, 1995, President Jiang Zemin delivered a speech
titled "Continue to strive for the accomplishment of the great
cause of reunifying the motherland", in which he set forth an
eight-point proposal for the resolution of the Taiwan issue.
</P>
<P>
"Experience of the past three years has fully proved that
President Jiang's speech has both practically important and
historically profound significance," the editorial says.
</P>
<P>
It points out that adherence to the "one China" principle is
the core of the eight-point proposal, as well as the foundation
for developing cross-Straits relations and realizing peaceful
reunification.
</P>
<P>
"Any words or actions that oppose the 'one China' principle
are in fact attempts to split China," it says.
</P>
<P>
The editorial stresses that it is indispensable for China's
peaceful reunification and key to the further development of the
current cross-Straits relations to hold as soon as possible
political negotiations between the two sides across the Straits.
</P>
<P>
"Peaceful reunification is our basic principle. And there must
be a proper way to realize peaceful reunification, which we
believe is political negotiations across the Straits," the
editorial says, adding that the Communist Party of China has
always been seeking early negotiations.
</P>
<P>
It goes on to say that the concept of realizing peaceful
reunification step by step has reflected the flexible and
pragmatic nature of the Chinese government's policies, and that it
is in the common interests of both sides of the Straits to first
end their hostility through political negotiations.
</P>
<P>
It points out that whether the cross-Straits negotiations can
happen depends on how much sincerity the Taiwan authorities have
in improving the cross-Straits relations.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that the Taiwan authorities can make a serious
response to our suggestions and proposals, and take concrete steps
to discuss with us on the procedures of political negotiations,"
it says.
</P>
<P>
It says that the rapid development of world economy has posed
challenges and also offered opportunities to both sides across the
Taiwan Straits in terms of economy, and that the Taiwan
authorities should not allow political differences to stand in the
way of economic cooperation across the Straits.
</P>
<P>
It also notes that the Chinese government fully respect Taiwan
compatriots' demand to develop political democracy, as well as their
wishes for the cross-Straits relations to maintain stability and
continue to develop.
</P>
<P>
"In fact, once the motherland is reunified under the principle
of 'one country, two systems', the interests of the Taiwan
compatriots won't be harmed by any means, and no change will take
place in their current way of life," it stresses.
</P>
<P>
"We believe the Taiwan compatriots will surely have a better
understanding of the 'one country, two systems' principle from the
convincing facts in Hong Kong after its return to the motherland,"
it adds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
