<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Astronomers Discovers New Type of Solar Activity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 26 (Xinhua) -- An international team of
astronomers, led by Dr. Richard Harrison of the Rutherford
Appleton Laboratory in Britain, has discovered a new type of solar
activity.
</P>
<P>
Short-lived flashes, which astronomers called blinkers, have
been found erupting sporadically over the surface of the Sun, the
Royal Astronomical Society (RAS) said today in a press notice.
</P>
<P>
The blinkers were detected by the Coronal Diagnostic
Spectrometer on board the European Space Agency's Solar and
Heliospheric Observatory(SOHO), according to the RAS.
</P>
<P>
These flashes are distributed over the entire Sun and are
visible for several minutes, each of them about the size of the
Earth.
</P>
<P>
The blinkers appear to be rather insignificant since they emit
only one millionth the energy of a solar flare.
</P>
<P>
Astronomers said that the new discovery may help to resolve two
outstanding problems in solar physics.
</P>
<P>
The blinkers may represent sites of plasma heating or particle
acceleration, astronomers said, which they thought may explain how
the Sun ejects the solar wind and why there is a big difference in
temperature between the outer atmosphere and the surface of the
Sun.
</P>
<P>
The blinkers seem to be the visible representation of a
transient process which is basic to the way the solar atmosphere
works, astronomers said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980127.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
