<HEADLINE> HSBC Keeps Status As UK's Biggest Company </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 26 (Xinhua) -- HSBC Holdings retains its status
as Britain's biggest company in the 1998 edition of The Times 1000
published here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
With capital employed of 26.9 billion pounds (43.04 billion
U.S. dollars), HSBC remains above Shell Transport and Trading and
is the flag carrier for the financial sector which dominates the
latest UK rankings.
</P>
<P>
No fewer than five banking groups are in the top ten companies
and there are 15 financial groups, consisting of banks and
insurance companies, in the top 50, according to the publication.
</P>
<P>
Martin Barrow, editor of The Times 1000, said: "Consolidation
of the financial sector has elevated the status of banks,
insurance companies and building societies, not just in Britain
but also in continental Europe and America."
</P>
<P>
Shell, the British half of the Royal/Dutch Shell group, is
ranked second in the UK. With capital employed of 20.99 billion
pounds (33.58 billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The company remains marginally ahead of BP, which has capital
employed of 20.55 billion pounds (32.88 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Abbey National, the former building society, has narrowed the
gap on BP and Shell after the purchase of National &AMP; Provincial,
and is ranked fourth, with capital employed of 20.1 billion pounds
(32.16 billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
BP is fifth, with capital employed of 17.5 billion pounds (28
billion U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
