<HEADLINE> Intel to Cut Chip Prices by About One Third </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, January 26 (Xinhua) -- The world largest chip maker Intel
Corporation has announced that it would cut its chip prices by
about one third on average worldwide with immediate effect, the
German news agency DPA reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made by Joachim Rissmann, a senior manager
of Intel's German subsidiary, in an interview with the DPA. The
price cuts were aimed to boost demand on the PC market, Rissmann
said.
</P>
<P>
According to Rissmann, Intel would also launch series
production of the 333 megahertz Pentium II processor soon on the
basis of the 0.25-micrometer technology instead of the current
0.35-micrometer technology.
</P>
<P>
He said that Intel had invested billions of dollars in new
factories in the United States and Ireland to introduce the new
technology which would enable the production of more powerful
processors for new multimedia applications.
</P>
<P>
The 333-megahertz Pentium II would be introduced to the market
with a price tag of 722 dollar, Rissmann said, adding that the
price for 233 Pentium II processor would be cut by 33 percent to
268 dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
