<HEADLINE> Expert Suggests to Pool $8.5bn for SADC Programs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, January 26 (Xinhua) -- The 14-member Southern African
Development Community (SADC) is trying to pool 8.5 billion U.S.
Dollars for the 500 programs planned by the regional
organization.
</P>
<P>
Prega Ramsary, the SADC chief economist said here Monday that
more efforts should be made to collect money from SADC member
countries, so as to change the trend of relying mainly on foreign
sources.
</P>
<P>
Ramsary estimated that about 80 percent of the fund for SADC
programs under way are from international communities, a trend
that must be changed.
</P>
<P>
As for the 48 energy programs which costs about 924 million
U.S. Dollars, for instance, 627 million Dollars have been
secured, but 96 percent of the fund come from outside SADC, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The economist said that the 83 agricultural programs which
need about 518 million Dollars, are employing 83 percent of their
money from outside, he said.
</P>
<P>
SADC is made up by South Africa, Angola, Botswana, Lesotho,
Malawi, Mauritius, Mozambique, Namabia, Democratic Congo,
Seychelles, Swaziland, Tanzania, Zambia and Zimbabwe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
