<HEADLINE> Loyalist Party Leaves N.Irish Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 26 (Xinhua) -- One of the pro-British
Protestant parties in the Northern Ireland peace talks, the Ulster
Democratic Party (UDP), announced on Monday it would quit from the
talks on the future of Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
The party was in danger of being expelled from the process
because of its close links with a paramilitary group, the Ulster
Freedom Fighters (UFF), which last week admitted breaking its
ceasefire to murder a number of Roman Catholics.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the decision, party leader Gary McMichael told a
news conference that he was not willing to see his party
"humiliated" by being thrown out of the talks when they resumed
Monday in London.
</P>
<P>
But he said the party was still committed to the peace process
although it stayed away from the talks.
</P>
<P>
"We fully expect to be expelled from this process. We are not
walking away. We want back into the negotiations, with the same
power as all the other parties, as quickly as possible," he said.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of parties for talks disagreed on whether it
was up to them or to the government to decide whether the UDP
should be expelled for links with terrorist groups responsible for
the killings in the past few weeks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
