<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Botswana to Get Cellular Phone Links </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 26 (Xinhua) -- Botswana will have its
first cellular telephone links by May and a complete network by
the end of the year, the Botswana Telecommunications Authority
(BTA) said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Two 15-year operation licenses, 1.29 million Rand (262,000
U.S. Dollars) each, would be issued to two joint partnerships to
build the network, South African Press Association quoted BTA
spokesman Claes Rosvall as saying.
</P>
<P>
One partnership involves Portuguese Telecom, a Zimbabwean
company and a Botswana company and the other involves French
Telecom and five Botswana companies.
</P>
<P>
Both operators are required to establish a network covering
the country's rail and road network from Lobatse in the south to
Francistown in the North, Rosvall said.
</P>
<P>
Besides, one operator should also cover the trans-Kalahari
highway, and the other the northern tourist areas of Maun and
Kasane, he said. The networks should be accessible to all users.
</P>
<P>
The deals also require that operators offer fax and data
services and charge cheaper call rates than South Africa.
</P>
<P>
French Telecom said his company could set up a network in
Gaborone, Botswana capital, within four months after obtaining a
license, and could cover most of the country within a year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
