<DOCNO> XIE19980127.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-26 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Defends Construction of Air Base </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, January 26 (Xinhua) -- The Cypriot government Monday
defended its construction of a military air base in Cyprus after
Turkey lodged protest against it.
</P>
<P>
Government spokesman Manolis Christofides said at his daily
press briefing Monday that the military air base near the western
coastal town of Paphos belongs to the Republic of Cyprus and the
stationing of Greek military aircraft there would depend on
developments.
</P>
<P>
"The base, to be inaugurated in March in the presence of the
Greek defense minister, will be named after the late Greek
Premier Andreas Papandreou, to honor him as the man who helped
consolidate our defense pact with Greece," Christofides said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said "it is our duty to boost our defenses and
the pact with Greece is our reply to the unprecedented upgrading
of the Turkish military."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus had completed the construction of the air base which
will be used by the Greek air force planes following the Cypriot
presidential elections scheduled for February 8.
</P>
<P>
Asked if Greek fighters would be stationed at the newly-built
air base, the spokesman said "if the prevailing situation
necessitates their permanent presence here, then they will be here
permanently."
</P>
<P>
The decision to have Greek aircraft at the base lies with the
governments of Cyprus and Greece and any needs that may arise, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus and Greece agreed upon a joint defense pact in November
1993, under which Greece provides Cyprus with military assistance
in case Cyprus is attacked.
</P>
<P>
Turkey said that it would protest the delivery of the air base
to the U.N. Secretary-General and the Security Council, while
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash warned he would "break the
wings" of Greek aircraft that may be deployed at the base.
</P>
<P>
"The base does not belong to Greece, it belongs to the
Republic of Cyprus to serve its defense purposes and facilitate
those powers which, in accordance with the 1960 treaties, have an
obligation to protect the integrity and the independence of the
Republic from outside attacks," Christofides said.
</P>
<P>
The Treaty of Guarantee, signed in 1960 when the island gained
independence from the British colonial rule, stipulates that
Greece, Britain and Turkey are the three guarantor powers of
Cyprus' independence, sovereignty and territorial integrity.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the island in the wake
of a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has been maintaining a 35,000-strong troops in Cyprus'
northern areas, where the Turkish Cypriots declared in 1983 a
breakaway Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus, which was
recognized only by Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980127.0039 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
