<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Varsity Students Threaten to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 26 (Xinhua) -- Just as last week's food riots
was settling, University of Zimbabwe (UZ) students announced
Monday that they will take to the streets Tuesday to protest
against the recent steep rises in the prices of most basic goods.
</P>
<P>
The students said in a statement distributed at campus, bus
termini and supermarkets that there was no reason for people to
go back to work when the prices of mealie meal, cooking oil,
bread and other basic commodities had actually not been reduced.
</P>
<P>
Police Spokesman Superintendent Wayne Bvudzijena said, "we
believe this document, with many others distributed during the
disturbances of January 19 and 20, are coming from the same
source. They should be ignored in their entirety."
</P>
<P>
"May we remind members of the public that it is an offense to
print or distribute any pamphlet which is likely to create public
disorder," he said.
</P>
<P>
He urged individuals and companies receiving fax messages
calling for people to stay away from work or incite violence to
send these faxes to their nearest police station.
</P>
<P>
"We, however, support the demonstration that the students at
campus intend to stage," he said, adding, "we will be behind them
if they feel that the nation is being short changed, but what we
do not want is the repeat of last week's looting."
</P>
<P>
The riots which started in Harare and Chitungwize last Monday
spread to other towns, leaving a trail of looting and destruction
of property worth millions of Dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
