<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Addis to Host Forum to Attract Capital for Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, January 26 (Xinhua) -- A two-day international
meeting, ''the Addis forum'' will be held here on March 8-9, 1998
to attract capital for Africa.
</P>
<P>
This was announced at a press conference held here on Monday
afternoon by the organizing committee which was sponsored by a
group of organizations and international firms including
Corporate Council on Africa, Global Coalition for Africa,
Sheraton Addis, Gulf International Bank, International Pepsi-Cola
Bottler Investments Ltd, US-Saudi Arabian Business Council and
World Times.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the press conference, members of the organizing
committee said ''the Addis forum'' was created to attract global
capital to Africa and to promote and encourage business and other
productive activities in Africa.
</P>
<P>
To that effect, the organizing committee said, the forum will
help attract international and domestic attention to Africa's
economic potential and business opportunities.
</P>
<P>
According to the committee, the forum is the first in series
of conferences in Africa and it will provide a mechanism for
foreign business executives, African governmental entities and
African business people to hold a policy dialogue aimed at
addressing perceived impediments to attracting capital to Africa.
</P>
<P>
The committee said, the committee has sent invitations to 11
heads of states of African countries, including Uganda, Botswana,
Eritrea, Malawi, Mali, Morocco, Tanzania, Tunisia, Ghana Zimbabwe
and Cote d'Ivoire.
</P>
<P>
The 1997 world investment report published by the U.N.
Conference on Trade and Development states that foreign direct
investment (FDI) rose by 10 percent in 1996 to a record of 349
billion U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
However, of the 349 billion Dollars in FDI, developing
countries received 129 billion Dollars, only 5.3 billion Dollars
flowed to Africa and Africa's share of FDI thus represent 1.5
percent of global FDI and 4.1 percent of developing world FDI.
This represents Africa's lowest share of FDI since the early
1980s. 
</P>
</TEXT>
