<HEADLINE> European Shares Lifted by a Firmer Wall Street </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 26 (Xinhua) -- Major stock markets in Europe
stayed in narrow trading ranges earlier on Monday until a firmer
opening on Wall Street, which is supported by U.S. President Bill
Clinton's new denial of the alleged sex scandal and news of a big
computer industry merger.
</P>
<P>
On the London market, dealers emerged from the trenches after a
better-than-expected start on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
The FTSE 100 index of leading British shares, which kicked off
the week with a cautious start, was boosted by news of the 9.6
billion U.S. dollars merger of computer giants Compaq and Digital.
</P>
<P>
The market closed 55.8 points higher at 5,237.2, lifted in late
trade by President Clinton's outright denial on television of the
sex claims made against him.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, German shares' floor trading, which ends before
Wall Street opens, ended 12.53 points lower at 4,224.78 on the
DAX-30 index.
</P>
<P>
Investors were shying away from the market, due to the dollar's
fall against the Deutschmark, with most individual shares lower,
traders said.
</P>
<P>
The CAC-40 index in Paris closed at 3,000.47, up 34.32 points,
lifted by the twin effects of an improving dollar and solid gains
on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
Traders said that market confidence returned as the dollar rose
from its morning low against the franc. 
</P>
