<HEADLINE> World PC Shipments up 15 Percent in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 26 (Xinhua) -- Worldwide personal computer
factory shipments grew 15 percent in 1997, with major U.S. PC
manufacturers leading the way with strong performances, the
International Data Corporation (IDC) reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The PC market maintained the solid growth in the fourth quarter
which saw a 14 percent surge compared to the third quarter, or a
21 percent increase over the same quarter 1996, the
Massachusetts-based IDC said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
U.S. PC shipments grew 19 percent and the European market was
up 15 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Shipments of leading U.S. companies Compaq and Hewlett-Packard
grew 47 percent and 65 percent respectively in 1997 and their
growths for the fourth quarter stood at 40 percent and 55 percent
respectively.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese market remained weak in the second half of the
year, with losses in the third and fourth quarters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
