<HEADLINE> Africa's Industrialization Lopsided, Says UNIDO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 26 (Xinhua) -- Industrialization in sub-Saharan
Africa has been lopsided with only six states contributing about
three quarters of manufacturing value added (MVA), according to
the U.N. Industrial Development Organization (UNIDO).
</P>
<P>
Only South Africa accounted for 58 percent of the MVA of
Africa south of the Sahara, while the other five, including
Cameroun, Cote d'Ivoire, Kenya, Nigeria and Zimbabwe, accounted
for 16.5 percent, UNIDO said, quoted by the News Agency of
Nigeria today.
</P>
<P>
"Moreover, four-fifths of sub-Saharan Africa's industrial
production is classified as low-technology, while the shares of
capital intensive, hi-tech sectors have declined," UNIDO said in
the latest edition of its newsletter.
</P>
<P>
The organization urged African government policy makers and
aid agencies to map out a new industrial strategy for the 21st
century.
</P>
<P>
It said despite very limited successes recorded in some
fields, structural adjustments had failed to reverse what it
termed de-industrialization or to create right policies for
industrial development through the private sector and new global
parterships. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980127.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
