<HEADLINE> Egypt Calls for US Support in Economic Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 26 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
on Monday called for bigger involvement of American private
sectors in supporting Egypt's economic development drive.
</P>
<P>
The president made the statement during a meeting with Egyptian
members of the Egyptian-American Presidents' Council which
convened here, the Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The Council was formed under the initiative of Mubarak and
U.S. Vice President Al Gore for trade partnership in March
1994. It groups 15 top executives from each side.
</P>
<P>
"The Council, firstly, should continue its role in Egypt's
economic liberalization process and expanding privatization
measures," said Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
At his meeting with the Egyptian side of the Council, the
president said that Egypt's economic progress is "preconditioned
on effecting tangible changes" in the Egyptian economy and the
Egyptian-American relations in general.
</P>
<P>
According to a communique released following the meeting,
Mubarak said the Council has played an important role in
establishing the bridges between the private sectors of both Egypt
and the U.S.
</P>
<P>
"It is acting as a catalyst in building the bridges between the
two economies that will make transfer of technology, know-how,
managerial skills and investments possible -- indeed, necessary,"
said the communique.
</P>
<P>
According to an American member of the Council, the U.S. has
only two other bodies of this kind, one with Russia and and the
other with South Africa.
</P>
<P>
The Egypt-U.S. Presidents' Council, decided in June 1997 to
begin talks on the possibility of drawing up a free trade
agreement between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Current U.S. investment in Egypt accounts for only 6 percent
of total foreign investments in the country. 
</P>
