<HEADLINE> Smile Train Project Launched in New York </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 26 (Xinhua)-- A joint bold new initiative aimed
at providing reconstructive surgery to indigent children in developing
countries around the world was launched here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The project named "The Smile Train" was announced by Charles B.
Wang, chairman of Computer Associates International, Dr. William
Magee Jr, co-founder and chairman of the U.S. Operation Smile, and
Brian Mullaney, Director of Operation Smile, at a press conference
at the Asian Society.
</P>
<P>
The Smile Train, loaded with surgical equipment, computers and
medical supplies, will carry teams of Operation Smile volunteers on
missions to small villages and towns.
</P>
<P>
The train is expected to start in China in early 1999, Mullaney
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Smile Train volunteers from China and around the world will work
side by side with local surgeons and nurses as they operate on
hundreds of children at each stop, he added.
</P>
<P>
The project has raised more than 18 million U.S. dollars including
the contributions of 10 million U.S. dollars from Wang and 1 million
from Microsoft's Bill Gates.
</P>
<P>
It has also garnered the support of government leaders from around
the globe, including Chinese President Jiang Zemin, former U.S.
President George Bush, and retired U.S. Army General Colin Powell,
Wang said.
</P>
<P>
The Smile train is scheduled to stay in China for five years. The
goals of the five-year prototype test include visiting 100 villages and
small towns, recruiting, training and supporting 100 partner hospitals,
training 10,000 medical professionals and leaving behind 15 million
U.S. dollars worth of medical equipment.
</P>
<P>
Mullaney estimated that the total budget of the project in China
would be some 30 million U.S.dollars.
</P>
<P>
After its initial success, the Smile Train will go to other
developing countries including Kenya and India, Mullaney disclosed.
</P>
<P>
The non-profit organization Smile Operation was founded in 1982
by the husband-and -wife team of Dr. Magee, a plastic surgeon, and
Katheleen Magee, a nurse and clinical social worker.
</P>
<P>
Working with volunteer professionals, donated equipment and
supplies, Operation Smile provides free reconstructive surgery to
children and young adults in developing countries and the United
States, liberating them from disfiguring conditions such as cleft
palates, cleft lips, tumors, burns, and scars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980127.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
