<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Security Council Urges Parties Concerned to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, January 26 (Xinhua) -- The Security Council of
the United Nations today unanimously adopted a resolution, calling
on the parties concerned to cooperate with international community
so as to complete the identification process timely in Western
Sahara.
</P>
<P>
The move came after the Security Council reviewed the latest
report by the UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan on Western Sahara.
</P>
<P>
In its resolution, the Security Council approved the
development of the engineering unit required for demining
activities and of the additional administration staff required to
support the deployment of military personnel suggested by the
Secretary-General in his report to the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
The Council expressed its intention to consider positively the
request for the remaining additional military and civilian police
assets for the United Nations Mission for the Referendum in
Western Sahara, as soon as the Secretary-General reports that the
identification process has reached a stage which makes the
deployment of these assets essential.
</P>
<P>
It urged the the Popular Front for the Liberation of Saguia
el-hamra and Rio De Oro (POLISARIO Front) and Morocco to cooperate
with the special representative of the secretary-General and to
cooperate further with the Special Identification Commission in
order that the identification process can be completed in a timely
fashion in accordance with the Settlement Plan and the agreements
reached between the parties for its implementation.
</P>
<P>
Western Sahara had been a Spanish colony until 1976 when Spain
withdrew and released itself from international responsibility
over the territory. The territory was subsequently occupied by
Morocco, a move which was opposed by POLISARIO Front. The
POLISARIO Front took up arms against Moroccan forces.
</P>
<P>
Following diplomatic initiatives by the Organization of African
Unity and the United Nations, the Security Council approved a
Settlement Plan for Western Sahara in 1990. Under the plan, there
would be a ceasefire, and a transitional period during which the
Special Representative of the Secretary-General would be in charge
of all matters relating to the referendum, assisted by the United
Nations Mission for the Referendum in Western Sahara.
</P>
<P>
The plan was eventually bogged down by the two parties'
differences on certain groups of people to be included in the
referendum.
</P>
<P>
A breakthrough was achieved last year when a new Special envoy
of the Secretary-general brought the two parties together and they
agreed to resume the identification process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
