<HEADLINE> S. Africa, EU to Resume Trade Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 26 (Xinhua) -- A high-level official
delegation from the European Commission, the executive body of
the European Union (EU), has been in South Africa for a new round
of talks toward a free trade agreement between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
The talks will be held in Pretoria Wednesday and Thursday,
said an EU statement.
</P>
<P>
"On the agenda for these talks are issues relating to tariff
liberalization and other trade aspects," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"During the latest round held in Brussels in December 1997,
the parties made significant progress on issues ranging from the
movement of capital to competition policy."
</P>
<P>
During talks earlier last year, South African negotiators
proposed that the agreement between the two regions should cover
all trade within a period of 10 to 12 years, and that the EU
should phase down its tariffs faster than South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Negotiations for a free trade agreement between the two sides
started as early as in 1994. It is believed that a comprehensive
agreement will be reached in mid-1998 between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
The 15-member EU block is South Africa's largest trading
partner. 
</P>
</TEXT>
