<HEADLINE> Iranian Missile Plan Poses Threat to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 26 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu said Monday that the building of Iranian
ballistic missiles arsenal could constitute the greatest threat
to Israel.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a special session of Israeli Knesset (parliament)
State Audit Committee, Netanyahu said that the Iranians were
moving ahead with the development of long-range ballistic
missiles, which reportedly would have a range of 3,000 kilometers,
capable of hitting Israel.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the danger Iranian long-range-missile
developing plan could pose to Israel is the greatest since the
founding of the Jewish country in 1948.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister also accused the Russian scientists of
helping the Iranians, adding that without this aid Teheran could
not develop the weapon system.
</P>
<P>
During his trip to Washington last week, Netanyahu discussed
the Iranian threat with both the United States President Bill
Clinton and Vice President Al Gore, hoping that the U.S. would
exert pressure on Russia to stop its technical aid to Iran.
</P>
<P>
But Netanyahu also said that Israel is preparing for the
possibility, that the political efforts to prevent Iran from
acquiring long-range ballistic missiles, would fail.
</P>
<P>
"We are presently engaged in a political effort to stop the
Iranians, this is not simply a lobby. We are talking about our
lives and our very existence. We are also taking the required
measures to stop this threat, " he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that if Iranian President Mohammad Khatami really
wanted to improve relationship with the United States, the first
thing he should do is to halt the development of the long-range
ballistic missiles, which are offensive.
</P>
<P>
Commercial and military ties between Israel and Iran gave way
to belligerence after the 1979 Islamic revolution in Iran.
</P>
<P>
Israel has been accusing Tehran of developing nuclear and other
non-conventional weapons to point at the Jewish state and of
arming Hezbollah (Party of God) guerrillas who have been fighting
Israeli occupation troops in south Lebanon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
