<HEADLINE> Turkey Calls for Dialogue with Greece on Disputes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, January 26 (Xinhua) -- Turkey said on Monday that a
constructive dialogue may be the best way to settle disputes
between Turkey and Greece.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Foreign Ministry spokesman Necati Utkan said at a
weekly press conference that Turkey has made its views on the
issue very clear on many occasions.
</P>
<P>
This is believed to be in response to the remark made by Greek
Foreign Minister Theodoros Pangalos last week that Greece intends
to bring the case to the International Court of Justice.
</P>
<P>
"We are open to a third party mediation, including the courts,
but the two sides concerned have to decide which issues require
that," Utkan said.
</P>
<P>
He said that Turkey's earlier suggestion that a dialogue
mechanism be set up by the two sides is still valid, adding that
Ankara is waiting for "a positive and constructive response from
Greece."
</P>
<P>
Stressing that Turkey attached special importance to the
settlement of the Turco-Greek disputes, the spokesman said it is
not realistic to try to solve each problem through different means.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Greece, both members of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization, have long been at odds over some issues, including
airspace limit, sovereignty over islets in the Aegean, its sea-bed
resources as well as the thorny Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
Greece, with support of many nations of the European Union, of
which Greece is a member state, favors a judicial settlement in
the International Court of Justice.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, however, has always held that the two countries should
solve their problem through bilateral talks which are also open to
a third party.
</P>
<P>
Turkish and Greek warplanes and naval vessels are frequently
involved in minor frictions over and in the Aegean Sea, touching
off accusations time and again.
</P>
<P>
Their disputes over an uninhabited islet in the eastern Aegean
almost brought the two neighboring countries to the brink of an
armed conflict in early 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
