<HEADLINE> Greece Rejects Bilateral Dialogue with Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, January 26 (Xinhua) -- Greece today turned down a
proposal by neighboring Turkey to have bilateral political
dialogue between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Greek government spokesman Dimitris Reppas said today that
Athens would not discuss issues that had already been settled on
the basis of international treaties or international law.
</P>
<P>
He added that any discussion of those issues before Turkey
recognized the jurisdiction of the international court at the
Hague would be held "in a vacuum."
</P>
<P>
Commenting on statements by Greek Foreign Minister Theodoros
Pangalos on Sunday that disputes between Greece and Turkey could
be solved by seeking recourse to international organizations,
Reppas said that Pangalos just tried to tell Turkey that if it
believed it had any problem with Greece, it should refer those
issues to the international court rather than resort to
"aggressive and provocative" military action.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that Greece's stance towards Turkey had not
changed, namely a step-by-step approach to differences with
Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Greece and Turkey, two rivalries for decades,
have been worsening in recent months following Turkey's failure to
become the European Union's prospective candidate and continued
military exercises by the two countries in the eastern Aegean Sea.
</P>
