<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Liberians Saddened by ECOMOG's Departure: Troop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 26 (Xinhua) -- Liberians are unhappy with the
ongoing withdrawal of the West African Peace-keeping Force
(ECOMOG) from their home country, the ECOMOG chief said here
Monday.
</P>
<P>
"They are not happy that we are reducing our troops. They like
Nigerian soldiers," said Maj.-Gen. Timothy Shelpidi, the newly
appointed ECOMOG force commander on his way to Liberia.
</P>
<P>
"We are reducing troops right now. There is not much happening
in Liberia except in Monrovia," he said, quoted by the News
Agency of Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
"Where there is nothing happening, there is no point having
soldiers in that country," he added.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria, a major contributor of materials and financial and
human resources for the peace keeping operations in Liberia,
began pulling out its troops from that country last December,
with the arrival of about 1,200 soldiers.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG troops were sent to Liberia in 1990 in the heat of the
civil war which was ignited by the battle launched by former
warlord and the current president Charles Taylor against the
previous government.
</P>
<P>
The sub-regional force has helped end the seven-year bloody
civil war which claimed the lives of 150,000 people, displaced
about one million others and destroyed the national economy.
</P>
<P>
The peace-keepers also provided security for a successful
election that brought Taylor to the nation's top seat.
</P>
<P>
Several west African countries have dispatched their troops to
join the ECOMOG contingent, which is expected to leave the
country next week.
</P>
<P>
According to reports, crowds of about 12,000 people assembled
in the capital Monrovia Sunday morning at a farewell party
marking the departure of ECOMOG.
</P>
<P>
They held banners and flags saying, "ECOMOG, we love you."
"Thank you, ECOMOG" and "Farewell, our west African friends".
</P>
<P>
Elsewhere in the city and surrounding towns, people gathered
around the radio sets all day listening to a live broadcast of
the parade by two local radio stations.
</P>
<P>
Under a peace accord that brought to an end the Liberian civil
war, ECOMOG will be involved in the restructuring and training of
Liberia's post-war army.
</P>
<P>
But Taylor reportedly did not want ECOMOG to be involved in
the restructuring and training of the Liberian armed forces,
saying that it was his constitutional right to do the job by
himself.
</P>
<P>
There are also reports that Taylor has begun training soldiers
of his former warring faction to replace members of the armed
forces of Liberia recently demobilized.
</P>
<P>
However, Shelpidi dismissed the reports, saying that he was
not aware of it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
