<HEADLINE> Chinese Foreign Ministry Says China Worried About Tensions in Gulf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 27 (Xinhua) -- China's Foreign Ministry
Spokesman Zhu Bangzao said today that China is deeply concerned
about tensions caused by UN weapons inspections in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
He said that China is asking all parties concerned to resolve
their disputes through dialogues and other peaceful ways to
avoid any further deteriorating situation that could affect the
peace and stability of the region.
</P>
<P>
He said that China believes that disputes between countries
should be resolved on the basis of the UN Charter and
international norms and opposes the frequent use of force or the
threat of force.
</P>
<P>
China maintains that Iraq should implement UN resolutions
completely and effectively, but at the same time, Iraq's concern
about its sovereignty and security should be respected by the
international community and Iraq's efforts to implement UN
resolutions should get an objective and just evaluation, he said.
</P>
<P>
The continuation of problems left over from the Gulf Crisis for
the past seven or more years has caused some serious disasters and
had a bad impact on countries in the Gulf region, he said. China
sincerely hopes that all parties concerned will continue to
cooperate to solve these remaining problems as soon as possible
and restore stability and rebuild the region, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
