<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Supports Projects for Refugees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The European Union Tuesday
announced support for 50 projects in member states that provide
assistance to refugees.
</P>
<P>
The projects range from construction and refurbishment of
reception centers in southern Italy and the Netherlands to
assistance for the voluntary return of those persons who receive
temporary protection in the European Union.
</P>
<P>
Two programs with a budget of 13.75 million ECU were
established last year to facilitate these projects.
</P>
<P>
The 1998 budget amounts to another 16.75 million ECU to support
the reception and voluntary return of refugees.
</P>
<P>
European Commissioner for Justice Anita Gradin highlighted the
contributions the reception program could make in responding to
mass arrivals within the European Union of people fleeing crisis
regions.
</P>
<P>
"The commission has supported projects that will help member
states to ensure that asylum seekers and refugees are received
humanely," said the commissioner.
</P>
<P>
She said the reception centers in southern Italy are
experiencing a significant influx of refugees from Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"The commission also emphasized the importance of the voluntary
return program," said Gradin. "By using EU funds to support
projects which meet the needs of Bosnians who have found
protection in (EU) member states and now wish to return."
</P>
<P>
The voluntary repatriation program enables refugees to return
to Bosnia-Herzegovina and will equip them to make a major
contribution to the reconstruction and the rebuilding of civil
society.
</P>
<P>
The European Union is hosting training programs and skill
retraining courses for a wide range of returnees to Bosnia,
including medical professionals, teachers, mine clearance
specialists, construction workers, craftsmen, agricultural workers
and entrepreneurs who wish to set up small businesses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
