<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-27 15:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Schooling Provided for Egyptian Children Returned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Egypt Tuesday ordered speedy
arrangements for proper schooling for the children of Egyptians
sacked by Qatar, the victims of a growing row between Doha and
Cairo.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Minister of Education Hussein Kamel Bahauddin
announced some measures to facilitate the enrollment process for
the beleaguered parents, Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported
</P>
<P>
"If any document required is not available, a statement of the
required details will be obtained from the parents and the child
will be admitted in school without any difficulty," said the
minister.
</P>
<P>
As regards Egyptian teachers whose services have been
terminated by Qatar, they will return to the schools where they
had worked, he said.
</P>
<P>
This step was taken as Qatar is to lay off more Egyptian
expatriates amid the escalating the row with Egypt.
</P>
<P>
The Qatari Interior Ministry has decided to lay off large
numbers of Egyptian expatriates. The Qatari National
Telecommunications Authority on Sunday dismissed all its 74
Egyptian workers, bringing the number of Egyptians fired to
234 after tensions mounted between the two countries since
November 1997.
</P>
<P>
According to Egyptian diplomats in Doha, the rest of the 5,000
Egyptians working in Qatar's public sector can expect their
dismissal by summer if relations between the two countries do not
improve.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian Embassy in Doha decided to cancel the annual
ceremonies marking Eid el-Fitr to help Egyptians process their
documents and leave Qatar as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa has reiterated the
necessity that Qatar should stop all measures against Egyptians
working in this small rich Arab emirate.
</P>
<P>
Hiring Egyptian workers in Qatar was banned since November 1997
when relations between the two countries hit the lowest point as
Egypt decided to boycott the controversial Middle East and North
Africa economic conference held Doha to protest the Mideast peace
stalemate.
</P>
<P>
Tensions heightened as the two sides quarreled over alleged
Egyptian involvement in a failed coup in Doha in February 1996.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia's mediation in December between Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak and Qatari Emir Sheik Hamad Bin Khalifa al-Thani
failed to produce concrete results.
</P>
<P>
About 25,000 Egyptians are living in Qatar, whose foreign labor
accounts for two-thirds of the countrys' entire population. 
</P>
</TEXT>
