<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lucent Innovation Boosts Capacity of Fiber Networks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 27 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Lucent Technologies Inc.
has developed a system that can transmit as many as 400 billion
bits of date per second over a single strand of fiber, a spokesman
for the company said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The new development is a new achievement of Lucent in its race
to meet phone companies' demands for more robust transmission
capacity as internet and data traffic are growing a year.
</P>
<P>
The system, which delivers five times the bandwidth of current
systems, raises the standards for such systems, which use a
technology known as dense wavelength division multiplexing.
</P>
<P>
The new system, when configured to work with eight fibers, can
transmit as many as 3.2 trillion bits of data a second--the
equivalent of 90,000 encyclopedia volumes in one second, Lucent
said.
</P>
<P>
Lucent has planned to begin shipping the product world-wide in
the fourth quarter of this year. That could give competitors time
to develop and deploy their own rich transmission systems.
</P>
<P>
AT&AMP;T Corp. said Monday that it plans to deploy Lucent's new
system to double the capacity of its 40,000-mile fiberoptic
network by the end of the year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
