<HEADLINE> Lanterns Hanging High for Spring Festival </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Beijing has hundreds of giant
red lanterns, an auspicious sign, hanging along its main streets
for China's most important holiday, Spring Festival, which falls
on the 28th.
</P>
<P>
All provinces, autonomous regions, and cities across the
country were decorated in similar fashion as Spring Festival
approached.
</P>
<P>
Tian'anmen Square has some 300 lanterns forming a sort of
necklace and brightening up the whole area. On two corners on the
northern part, two red lanterns six meters in diameter and 13
meters high, the biggest in China, add to the holiday atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
A ceremonial archway with two dragons and two 100-meter strings
of light have bathed the square in light.
</P>
<P>
On Chang'an Avenue, which crosses the Square on the north, 60
strings of lanterns and glittering lights have been hung from pine
trees, and a hundred pagoda trees and 120 golden rain trees have
been decorated with lights, as have been 50 whitepine trees at the
Xinhua News Agency's main gate.
</P>
<P>
Lanterns of all sizes can also be seen along the city's main
shopping streets in Wangfujing, Xidan, and Dongdan.
</P>
<P>
According to the Chinese calendar, 1998 is the year of the
tiger, symbolizing vigor, energy, and good fortune. 
</P>
</TEXT>
