<HEADLINE> Cholera Spreads to Mozambique's Second Largest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Beira city, the second largest
city in Mozambique, was reported to have been hit by cholera
epidemic with 5 victims by Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
This is the first cholera record in Beira and the Sofala
province since the disease broke out in southern and central
Mozambique last August.
</P>
<P>
According to Antonio Francisco, head of the health authority
in Sofala province, the five patients are all from Macuti region
in Beira. He cited the low chlorine content in drinking water as
the main cause for the cholera outbreak in the region.
</P>
<P>
Cholera was first reported in Maputo, capital of Mozambique,
before it spread to the province of Maputo, Gaza, Inhambane and
Manica.
</P>
<P>
Since last August, a total of 10,955 people have fallen victim
to the epidemic, with 286 deaths. 
</P>
</TEXT>
