<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 3 Islamic Militants Sentenced to Death in Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 27 (Xinhua) -- A Cairo court on Tuesday passed
death verdicts to three Islamic militants convicted in the murder
of 26 policemen, largely known as the 33-member Major
Assassination case, the Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The State Supreme Security Court also sentenced four other
defendants to life imprisonment with hard labor, three to 15 years
in prison with hard labor and five to a ten-year imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
Three others were sentenced to five years in jail and the
remaining suspects were acquitted in the nine-month-long court
proceedings. Two terrorists that were at large had been shot in a
crossfire with the police.
</P>
<P>
The verdict was pronounced in a 10-minute session that was
attended by the foreign and local press under tight security.
</P>
<P>
Events of the Major Assassinations case involved 18 bloody
terrorist acts that were carried out by 33 terrorists from the
Destruction and Devastation group, a branch under the Islamic
Group, in the Upper Egyptian governorates of Sohag, Assiut and
Minya since 1994.
</P>
<P>
In addition to killing the policemen in 1993-94, they also were
accused of plotting to kill 46 other people, and attacks on
vehicles carrying foreigners in 1992 and 1994.
</P>
<P>
The death sentence first passed in December, has been approved
by Egypt's mufti, the chief government cleric.
</P>
<P>
Islamic militants have launched an anti-government campaign
since 1992. More than 1,300 people have been killed in the
violence. Most of the victims have been policemen or extremists.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
