<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Tiananmen Square on New Year's Eve </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of people from all
over the country gathered in Beijing's Tiananmen Square this
evening, on the eve of Spring Festival, the Chinese lunar new year.
</P>
<P>
Spring Festival is the most important holiday for the Chinese,
and the world's largest square was lit up with thousands of bulbs,
laser lights, and large red lanterns, a traditional symbol of
happiness and good luck in China.
</P>
<P>
The sight of the lights and lanterns even prompted many locals,
who usually stay home for a traditional family reunion feast, to
venture out to the square.
</P>
<P>
One of them, Ge Binyi, who had braved the bitter cold to come
out and fly a home-made kite in the square, was being followed by
a large group of kids who were shouting excitedly. "I feel so
happy," the 62-year-old man said, "our country is getting stronger
and our lives better year by year, and the lanterns symbolize an
even better year."
</P>
<P>
Three others, Lu Bo and his wife and child, who came from the
city of Yichang in central China, wandered around the square to
take pictures in front of every set of lights and decoration. Lu
said that it was the first time for them to come to Beijing to
celebrate Spring Festival, and although it will cost six to seven
thousand yuan, they can afford it because of salary increases.
</P>
<P>
Qi Zengju, a 74-year-old Beijing resident, said that the
colorful decorations on a 14-meter-high arch hung with red
lanterns symbolize reunification of the country, and that everyone
hopes for an early reunification of the motherland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
