<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU, Russia Hold First Cooperation Council Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Russia expressed support for
the planned enlargement of the European Union when the two sides
met Tuesday for their first cooperation council meeting.
</P>
<P>
Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov said his country has
no reason to oppose the bid by several central and eastern
European countries to join the EU.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook, whose country
is currently serving as the rotating presidency of the 15-nation
union, said his Russian counterpart expressed support for the
enlargement which is set to begin in March this year.
</P>
<P>
Poland, Hungary, the Czech Republic, Estonia, Slovenia and
Cyprus were chosen last December to be included in the first wave
of accession talks.
</P>
<P>
Cook and Primakov were joined in the council meeting by the
foreign ministers of all other European Union member states.
</P>
<P>
The one-day meeting was the first following the initiation last
December of the Partnership and Cooperation Agreement signed
between EU and the Russian Federation.
</P>
<P>
The cooperation council is intended to encourage high-level
discussions on a wide range of issues of common interest,
including political, economic and trade cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The meeting however did not produce any solid results though
the EU tried to persuade Russia to further open its markets, to
cancel quotas imposed on EU carpets, and to drop trans-Siberian
overflight right fees the EU claims are used as subsidies for the
Russian carrier Aeroflot.
</P>
<P>
Hans van den Broek, European commissioner in charge of central
and eastern European affairs, said the first cooperation council
meeting is expected to turn out a beginning rather than a
conclusion on consultation.
</P>
<P>
The European Union has become an important trade partner with
Russia in recent years, with 40 percent of the Russian trade in
goods going to the EU.
</P>
<P>
Also discussed at the meeting were bilateral relations,
anti-dumping policies, Russia's bid for accession to the World
Trade Organization, and cooperation in justice and home affairs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
