<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hungarian Police Uncover Counterfeit Money </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Hungarian newspapers reported
Tuesday that police in Nograd state discovered 75 million furint
(375,000 U.S. dollars) in counterfeit money.
</P>
<P>
The report said the fake bills were found inside a car during a
routine traffic check. The fake bills were still on large sheets
of paper and had not yet been cut into individual bills.
</P>
<P>
In the report, police claim the fake bills were manufactured by
the owner of a printing house and the owner of a trading company.
</P>
<P>
The report says the fake bills were extremely well made and are
difficult to distinguish from real money, even with the assistance
of precision instruments used to detect counterfeit money.
</P>
<P>
Police maintain the production of the counterfeit money is
related to the theft several years ago of special imported
printing paper which is used to print money. Police said the case
is still under investigation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
