<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Spending Several Billion Yuan on Yangtze River Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, January 27 (Xinhua) -- A large project to improve
shipping conditions at the mouth of the Yangtze River by clearing
and deepening the channel started today in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
The project is expected to cost three billion yuan (about 350
million US dollars) in its first phase, which will take three
years. In that time, the depth of the shipping channel there is
expected to go from 7 to 8.5 meters.
</P>
<P>
This will mean nearly 20 billion yuan in profits for Shanghai,
China's most important seaport, during the next two decades,
shipping experts predict. Last year, the port handled over 2.5
million standard containers.
</P>
<P>
The ultimate goal of the three-phase project is to lower depth
at the mouth to 12.5 meters to allow more than 100,000-tonnage
ships to enter Shanghai harbor.
</P>
<P>
Premier Li Peng wrote inscriptions for the project,
saying: "Improving the deepwater channel at the Yangtze River
mouth to help build Shanghai into a world economic center and
bring about a new leap of development in the Yangtze River delta."
</P>
<P>
Vice-Premier Wu Bangguo and Shanghai Mayor Xu Kuangdi attended
the project's opening ceremony, which was presided over by Huang
Zhendong, minister of communications.
</P>
<P>
Wu called this "a magnificent project that will last until the
next century,, one that shows China's improved shipping conditions
and a major step forward in developing Shanghai into an
international shipping center. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
