<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sampras Crashes out of Australian Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 27 (Xinhua) -- World number one Pete Sampras
lost his first set and then the match in a quarter-final of the
Australian Open on Tuesday in Melbourne, crashing 6-4, 6-2, 6-7,
6-3 to unseeded Slovak Karol Kucera.
</P>
<P>
Sampras, who was seeking for his 11th Grand Slam and his third
Australian Open trophy, never lost one single set before the
dismal clash in previous seven matches.
</P>
<P>
Kucera, ranked 20th in the world, kept press with his stormy
service game upon the Man of Mission who was will under his best
form.
</P>
<P>
The 23-year-old Kucera had never made a third-round appearance
of any grand slam tournament, but gave little chance to the
defending champion to come back to the game.
</P>
<P>
The Slovakian has won two tournaments this year - the Hopman
Cup team exhibition event in Perth and the Sydney International.
</P>
<P>
Chilean ninth seed Marcelo Rios is the other seed survives in
the men's draw.
</P>
<P>
Kucera had been in brilliant form leading into Tuesday night,
winning 14 out of 15 matches this month - in the Hopman Cup in
Perth, the Sydney international tournament which he won and here
at the Open.
</P>
<P>
Immediately after the match, he said he was looking forward to
playing Korda.
</P>
<P>
It will be the first time they have met in a professional
tournament.
</P>
<P>
"I'm happy to be in the semi-finals, and happy to be playing my
countryman almost - I hope to win," Kucera said.
</P>
<P>
"I had a very good preparation ... that's why I'm playing so
well now."
</P>
<P>
The unemotional Slovakian said he was in the best form of his
career and said he was still coming to terms with tonight's
amazing win.
</P>
<P>
"Maybe a little bit later, I will jump somewhere," he said in
reference to his apparent lack of excitement.
</P>
<P>
Kucera said Sampras had started very aggressively, but he had
been able to keep with the American's rhythm.
</P>
<P>
"Then I think he started to push a little harder and he started
to make some mistakes," Kucera said.
</P>
<P>
Sampras said he had been out-played Tuesday night and thought
he did not react well to Kucera's initial charge.
</P>
<P>
He agreed his forehand was also off, but offered no excuses.
</P>
<P>
"I got impatient out there and missed some shots," he
said. "There's no excuse, my hat's off to him, he played a great
match."  
</P>
</TEXT>
