<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading U.S. newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- The U.S. Republican leadership in Congress lined up behind
President Clinton's stance on Iraq, saying that the sex scandal
absorbing the White House should not be allowed to affect the way
the United States responds to a foreign policy problem.
</P>
<P>
-- President Clinton angrily denied that he had had sexual
relations with Monica S. Lewinsky, the former White House intern
whose tape-recorded accounts of an affair with him now threaten
his Presidency.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- At a moment of maximum political peril, President Clinton
plans tonight to open a national debate on the most sacred and
untouchable of government programs, Social Security. White House
officials confirmed Monday that a major theme of Clinton's State
of the Union address will be a plea to hold on to prospective
budget surpluses for shoring up Social Security against the
enormous tide of baby boom retirements that threaten its long-term
future.
</P>
<P>
-- More than 100 public prosecutors raided Japan's powerful
Ministry of Finance Monday, arresting two bank regulators on
bribery charges and combing through ministry records in an
unprecedented crackdown on collusion between government and
business.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- The U.S. State Department expressed interest in planned
legislation to step up deliveries of food and medicine to Cuba,
but said it remains committed to the 35-year-old embargo against
Cuba.
</P>
<P>
-- A U.S. astronaut will proceed with a four and a half months
stay aboard the Russian space station after he adjusted straps and
successfully donned his Russian-made spacesuit. He initially said
the suit, needed in any emergency, didn't fit. His Russian hosts
belittled the complaint by Andrew Thomas. 
</P>
