<HEADLINE> Chinese Earthquake Areas Welcome Lunar New Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Farmers in
earthquake-damaged parts of China's Hebei Province have received
coal, rice, flour, and alcohol from the local government for the
Spring Festival, China's lunar new year.
</P>
<P>
In the busy markets of Zhangjiakou Prefecture, farmers are
doing their shopping for their most important holiday of the year.
And the local government, to make sure they have enough dumplings,
the traditional food associated with Spring Festival, has provided
150,000 kilograms of flour, 100,000 kilograms of rice and 75,000
kilograms of pork.
</P>
<P>
In the most seriously affected areas, about 40,000 farmers have
moved into 10,000 newly-built houses and tents, on the doors of
which have appeared matching couplets expressing new year's
greetings, and government departments have inspected the houses
and tents to make sure they are safe and warm enough.
</P>
<P>
Sanitation workers have been busy clearing snow from the
highway to the prefecture, and policemen have been dealing with
traffic problems.
</P>
<P>
Local culture departments have prepared entertainment for the
farmers, and many of the heroic deeds during the quake-relief
effort have been woven into the performances.
</P>
<P>
The people of Beijing have been concerned about the lives of
the farmers in the earthquake areas, and trucks of rice, flour,
medicines, instant noodles, and dumplings left Beijing this
morning, bound for the areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
