the planned enlargement of the European Union when the two sides
met Tuesday for their first cooperation council meeting.
</P>
<P>
Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov said his country has
no reason to oppose the bid by several central and eastern
European countries to join the EU.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook, whose country
is currently serving as the rotating presidency of the 15-nation
union, said his Russian counterpart expressed support for the
enlargement which is set to begin in March this year.
</P>
<P>
Poland, Hungary, the Czech Republic, Estonia, Slovenia and
Cyprus were chosen last December to be included in the first wave
of accession talks.
</P>
<P>
Cook and Primakov were joined in the council meeting by the
foreign ministers of all other European Union member states.
</P>
<P>
The one-day meeting was the first following the initiation last
December of the Partnership and Cooperation Agreement signed
between EU and the Russian Federation. 
