<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kucera Beats Sampras </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Unseeded Slovakian Karol
Kucera produced the match of his life in Melbourne Tuesday night
to pull off the upset of this Australian tennis open, beating
world No.1 Pete Sampras in four sets.
</P>
<P>
Only last night, Andre Agassi said he would not bet against
Sampras winning his second-successive Australian title.
</P>
<P>
But reputation and odds counted for nothing to 23-year-old
Kucera, ranked 20th in the world, who harried and ran Sampras
around the court to win 6-4, 6-2, 6-7 (7-5), 6-3.
</P>
<P>
Kucera had never made it past the third round of a grand slam
tournament before this year, while Sampras had also won this open
in 1994 and this time had not dropped a set in the event before
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
The gallant Slovakian will meet sixth-seeded Petr Korda in the
semi-finals after the Czech rallied to beat fourth-seeded Swedish
Jonas Bjorkman earlier Tuesday at 3-6, 5-7, 6-3, 6-4, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
It was only the second time Kucera and Sampras had met in a
professional tournament, with Sampras winning their previous
encounter at Wimbledon in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Sampras was well off his game, making far too many unforced
errors, while Kucera was magnificent.
</P>
<P>
Kucera controled the tempo of the match from the outset,
breaking Sampras in the first game of the first set.
</P>
<P>
Sampras launched a spirited counter-attack in the third,
breaking back twice to force the tiebreak, and looked to be
gaining momentum early in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
But Kucera broke him in the sixth game and then held serve for
the match.
</P>
<P>
Kucera's serve was a dangerous weapon, with the Slovakian
firing down 18 aces to Sampras' seven, while the American star
made 46 unforced errors. The Slovakian only made 21. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
