<DOCNO> XIE19980127.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Efforts Urged to Step Up Tibet's Foreign Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 27 (Xinhua) -- China's International Business
Daily says that the Tibet Autonomous Region needs to improve
foreign trade to meet international challenges and rapid economic
growth.
</P>
<P>
It says that during the 1991-1995 period, foreign trade had an
average annual increase of 70 percent, with a trade volume of 540
million US dollars, nearly six times that of the previous
five-year period.
</P>
<P>
However, foreign trade is still limited to general merchandise
and processing trade, and the service trade, engineering, and
labor exports have not been tried, and export goods are mainly
primary products like wool and hand-made carpets, with little
added-value.
</P>
<P>
Border trade only accounted for 10 percent of the region's
total foreign trade and needs to be developed. These foreign trade
problems are related to the backward status of agriculture, the
geography, transportation difficulties, and a shortage of
qualified personnel.
</P>
<P>
Tibet needs to increase agriculture input, improve its
infrastructure, and produce major products with local
characteristics to create favorable conditions for foreign
trade. It needs to increase trade with countries other than Nepal,
where about 90 percent of its exports go. 
</P>
</TEXT>
