<DOCNO> XIE19980127.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barclays, Standard Banks in S. Leone Urged to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Scores of customers claiming
to have cheque and deposit accounts with Barclays and Standard
Chartered Banks in Sierra Leone Monday called for the reopening
of the international banks.
</P>
<P>
The two banks were closed down after the May 25 coup last year
which toppled the civilian government.
</P>
<P>
"I am virtually living as a destitute because I am now deep in
debt. I have to shut myself in and refuse to answer the door bell
fearing that people have come to collect their debts," said one
customer who has a large amount of money deposited in the
Barclays.
</P>
<P>
Maciama Turay, a petty trader, said she cannot send her
children to school because she cannot provide uniform, shoes and
lunch for them.
</P>
<P>
"We don't know whom to talk to. We have been in touch with
the Governor of the Central Bank but he said he could do very
little except facilitate our complaints to the headquarters of
both banks in London. This is a rough plight," she added.
</P>
<P>
Other customers of Barclays and Standard Chartered Banks said
they were now "financially displaced."
</P>
<P>
"My business is in ruins," said one customer while another
threatened legal action to gain access to his savings.
</P>
<P>
One of the hardest hit sector is the privately owned
educational institutions which cater for kindergartens and
primary school children.
</P>
<P>
"We have now put our teachers on half salaries until Barclays
reopens," said headmistress Elfrida Lewis of the Hope Preparatory
School.
</P>
<P>
Senior personnel of both Banks fled the country after the
coup, making it difficult to get transactions.
</P>
<P>
Both banks carry about 70 percent of all banking transactions
in the country while they have purchased millions of dollars of
Treasury Bonds and Bills from the Bank of Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Although they have been inoperative, both banks had kept all
their employees on their payroll until last week when Standard
Chartered reportedly sacked about 90 of its staff.
</P>
<P>
Barclays will shortly fire some 100 workers including some in
managerial positions.
</P>
<P>
Observers said both banks may be assessing the security
situation in the country before deciding whether to reopen their
doors or otherwise. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
