<DOCNO> XIE19980127.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Non-Communist Parties on Anniversary of President's Speech on Taiwan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Non-communist parties in China
and the All-China Federation of Industry and Commerce held a forum
today to mark the third anniversary of President Jiang Zemin's
speech on the reunification of the motherland or the Taiwan issue.
</P>
<P>
He Luli, vice-chairwoman of the National Committee of the
Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC) and
chairwoman of the Central Committee of the Revolutionary Committee
of the Chinese Kuomintang, presided over the forum.
</P>
<P>
She told the gathering that the Chinese people will not
tolerate any attempt to create "two Chinas" or "one China, one
Taiwan", and she urged the Taiwanese authorities to accept the
one-China position as soon as possible, make joint efforts to
improve cross-straits relations and contribute to the
reunification of the motherland.
</P>
<P>
She said that non-communist parties and the All-China
Federation of Industry and Commerce will continue to follow
Jiang's speech on the Taiwan issue, and make more links and
exchanges with people in Taiwan to increase understanding.
</P>
<P>
Cheng Siwei, chairman of the Central Committee of the China
Democratic National Construction Association, told the gathering
that President Jiang's Eight-Point Proposal expresses the desire
of all quarters, including his association, and the Taiwanese
authorities should respond to Jiang's proposal, hold negotiations,
and open direct postal, commercial and transport links at an early
date.
</P>
<P>
Jing Shuping, president of the All-China Federation of Industry
and Commerce, said that cross-straits economic and trade exchanges
are playing an important role in the economic prosperity of both
two sides, but that some obstacles mean that economic cooperation
can only be done in an indirect way and seriously hinder the
development of both sides.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that industrial and commercial sectors on
both sides will make an effort at economic cooperation and
contribute to the peaceful reunification of the motherland.
</P>
<P>
Others who addressed the forum include Wu Xiuping,
vice-chairman of the Central Committee of the China Democratic
League; Xu Jialu, chairman of the Central Committee of the China
Association for Promoting Democracy; Jiang Zhenghua, chairman of
the Central Committee of the Chinese Peasants' and Workers'
Democratic Party; Luo Haocai, chairman of the Central Committee of
the China Zhi Gong Party; Zhao Weizhi, vice-chairman of the
Central Committee of the Jiu San (September 3) Society; and Li
Minkuan, secretary general of the Central Committee of the Taiwan
Democratic Self-Government League. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
