<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian Minister: Preparation for Arab Summit Not </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa said Tuesday that no measure has been taken so far for
convening an Arab summit on Mideast peace but prospects of holding
it "are available," Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
This was stated by Moussa following the talks between Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak and Palestinian National Authority
President Yasser Arafat, who has been calling for such a summit.
</P>
<P>
The talks between the two leaders here touched on the Arab
action in face of the stalled peace process, said Moussa.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, Arafat and the Palestinian delegation
expounded the outcome of recent Washington talks with
U.S. President Bill Clinton, the Israeli proposals and the
U.S. stance, he said.
</P>
<P>
"It was clear that all Israeli proposals were not enough to
salvage the peace process," Moussa added.
</P>
<P>
The talks came within the context of consultations Egypt plans
to hold with a number of other Arab countries to discuss the
outcome of the meetings Clinton had with the Israeli and
Palestinian leaders in Washington last week.
</P>
<P>
During Tuesday's talks, Arafat, who arrived here Monday night,
informed Mubarak of the results of his tour of Britain and Arab
Maghreb region, including Mauritania, Morocco, Algeria and
Tunisia, on his way back from Washington.
</P>
<P>
In Algiers and London, the Palestinian leader called for
holding an emergency Arab summit to look into the latest
developments in the Arab world, with particular focus on the
Palestinian cause, and map out the next steps that should be taken
to confront the Mideast peace stalemate.
</P>
<P>
His appeal coincided with a statement by the Cairo-based Arab
League that backed any Arab call for holding a new Arab summit on
the grave conditions of the peace process and the failure of
Washington's peace overtures.
</P>
<P>
Upon arrival at the airport, Palestinian Planning and
International Cooperation Minister Nabil Shaath told reporters
that they are returning home from Washington "empty-handed."
</P>
<P>
"The Palestinians have implemented their part of all the
agreements (signed with Israel), but Israel destroyed everything
and offered nothing," he added.
</P>
<P>
Arafat has been voicing his frustration with the Washington
talks which he described as a "failure" and urging Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu to fulfill his obligations.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile in Washington, a spokesman for the Department of
State said the U.S. believes that the Arab countries have the
right to hold a summit to discuss the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. official said there are current talks with Israel and
the PNA in order to assess reactions of both sides to recent
U.S. proposals that try to "strike an acceptable balance" between
an Israeli withdrawal of troops from the West Bank and Palestinian
implementation of security measures.
</P>
<P>
Measures to be taken by the Palestinians according to the
U.S. proposals would involve exchanging intelligence information
with Israelis and shutting down religious and social institutions
that belong to the militant radical group Hamas, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peace talks have remained deadlocked
since last March when Israel started to build a new settlement in
Arab East Jerusalem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
