<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brundtland Nominated for WHO Director-General </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Dr. Gro Harlem Brundtland of
Norway was nominated here Tuesday to succeed Dr. Hiroshi Nakajima
as the Director-General of the World Health Organization (WHO),
becoming the first woman to lead the United Nations agency.
</P>
<P>
Brundtland, a 59-year-old physician, is a former Norwegian
prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Brundtland won 18 votes in the fourth round secret ballot of
the WHO's 32-member executive committee, defeating four other
rival candidates.
</P>
<P>
The nomination by the executive board has to be confirmed by
WHO member states in May, 1998, when the World Health Assembly
convenes in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
Brundtland will officially take up her post on July 21.
</P>
<P>
"I will start with internal reforms," she said, responding to
questions on what her first actions at the WHO would be. She said
she would focus on those in greatest need, "and the needs are
greatest in the developing world."
</P>
<P>
Nakajima, who served two five-year terms, had announced that he
would leave the agency in April. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
