<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Chief Executive Extends Lunar New Year Greetings to Citizens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Tung Chee Hwa, chief
executive of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) of
China, extended his warmest wishes to the Hong Kong citizens
Tuesday on the eve of the Lunar New Year.
</P>
<P>
In his televised Lunar New Year message, Tung and his wife,
Betty, wished all the HKSAR citizens good health and a prosperous
year.
</P>
<P>
This is the first Lunar New Year after the establishment of the
HKSAR on July 1, 1997, Tung noted.
</P>
<P>
The successful implementation of the principles of "one
country, two systems" and "Hong Kong people running Hong" have
been welcomed by the whole community, Tung said.
</P>
<P>
With the support of the Central People's Government and the
hard work of the Hong Kong people, the HKSAR has made a good
start, he added.
</P>
<P>
"We have drawn up long-term goals for the future development of
Hong Kong and we are now turning them into reality," Tung pointed
out.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the hardship resulting from the recent Asian
financial turmoil, Tung said the SAR government "will take all
possible steps to provide a helping hand."
</P>
<P>
The government is doing its best and will certainly take the
interests of the entire community into account despite the fact
that the measures now under consideration may not meet the needs
and aspirations of everyone, Tung said.
</P>
<P>
"Apart from doing our utmost to tackle the immediate problems,"
he added, "we will strive to lay a firm foundation for the
long-term development of Hong Kong."
</P>
<P>
The Asian financial turmoil gives Hong Kong an opportunity to
make quicker adjustments to some negative factors of Hong Kong's
economy, such as the soaring property prices, high inflation and
negative interest rates, Tung said.
</P>
<P>
"We must remain calm and collected to overcome these temporary
setbacks," he said. "Once this has been achieved, the foundations
for our future progress and prosperity will be further
strengthened."
</P>
<P>
He stressed that there are two things that the government must
do.
</P>
<P>
First the government should endeavor to work for the well-being
of the next generation. "Only by doing this shall we be able to
plan for Hong Kong's future with a new vision and commitment."
</P>
<P>
Second, he said, the government must regard the people of Hong
Kong as members of a large family, to ensure that the elderly, the
poor and the underprivileged are well cared for and are provided
with a sense of security.
</P>
<P>
Describing his post as the greatest honor given to him and the
greatest challenge of his life, Tung pledged to "exert every
effort to perform my duties and work hand in hand with you all
toward the 21st century."
</P>
<P>
Tung and his wife have sent a Lunar New Year greeting card to
the people of Hong Kong via the Internet and they will also tour
the Lunar New Year Fair at Victoria Park Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
On the Lunar New Year's Day, they will visit two homes for the
elderly in Tai Po and distribute presents to a gathering of
elderly people there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
