<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Pulled Down by Banks, Gold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Major banks pulled the
Australian stock market down Tuesday as investors renewed their
interest in gold stocks after a surge in the gold price overnight.
</P>
<P>
Brokers said investors were taking their money out of banks and
sitting on the sidelines, ready to buy back into the sector again
when the prices of bank stocks fell further.
</P>
<P>
Reynolds &AMP; Co.'s Peter Struk said Australian investors were a
"little bit wary" at the moment.
</P>
<P>
"The uncertainty with Asia, Hong Kong going to be closed for
the next few days for Chinese New Year and Clinton looking like he
may have to resign ... I think a combination of all that pulled
the market down," Struk said.
</P>
<P>
The All Ordinaries Index closed 19.4 points down at 2603.9.
</P>
<P>
Gold smashed through the 300-U.S.-dollar barrier in London
overnight after a strong rise on Friday but lost some ground to
close at 297.1 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Henderson Charlton Jones broker Philip Toop said that after a
promising start this morning the market picked up on the
negativity of last week's Asia-inspired nervousness and dropped
off.
</P>
<P>
"The whole market ended up a bit weaker," Toop said. "Ongoing
concern about Asia exposure has continued to dampen the sector."
</P>
<P>
The banking index finished the day down 124.1 points, or 2.28
percent, at 5327.1, led by ANZ bank which fell after Moody's
downgraded its rating outlook to negative.
</P>
<P>
ANZ slipped 32 cents to 9.38 Australian dollars, Westpac bank
35 cents to 9.72 Australian dollars, Commonwealth 22.7 points to
18.29 Australian dollars and National Australia Bank 42 cents to
19.77 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The All Industrials Index was down 40.4 points at 4463.4 while
the All Resources Index shaved off 1.5 points to 1120.5.
</P>
<P>
The gold index finished the day 32.6 points higher at 1062.
</P>
<P>
In Sydney gold bullion finished trading 8.95 U.S. dollars
stronger at 299.75 U.S. dollars, up from Friday's close at 298.35
dollars.
</P>
<P>
In the resource sector, BHP fell 20 cents to 13.87 Australian
dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 263.06 million shares worth 553.01
million U.S. dollars with falling stocks slightly overshadowing
rising stocks by 574 to 538.  
</P>
</TEXT>
