<HEADLINE> Russian President's Special Envoy Arrives in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris
Yeltsin's personal envoy to Iraq Victor Sivaliok arrived here
Tuesday afternoon on a brief visit to discuss the development of
situation with the Iraqi leaders.
</P>
<P>
In a statement released upon his arrival, Sivaliok, Russian
deputy foreign minister, said that he was assigned by Yeltsin on
an urgent mission to discuss with "our Iraqi friends" the
development of situation concerning Iraq at this particular time,
the Iraqi news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
He added that he was also entrusted with undertaking efforts to
find a way out of such situation through political and diplomatic
means.
</P>
<P>
The Russian envoy renewed his country's firm position of
rejecting the use of force against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
A week ago, U.N. chief arms inspector Richard Butler failed to
persuade Iraq to allow inspectors to enter presidential sites to
carry out work after three rounds of talks with Iraqi Deputy Prime
Minister Tariq Aziz.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has proposed to freeze any discussions or actions with
respect to the question of inspectors' access to presidential
sites before technical evaluation meetings come to an end in April.
</P>
<P>
The United States described the Iraqi proposal as unacceptable,
and has warned of military solution to the standoff between Iraq
and the U.N. Special Commission in charge of eliminating Iraq's
weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
However, Russia, France and China have said that they strongly
object to the use of force against Iraq and called for diplomatic
solution to the standoff. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
