<DOCNO> XIE19980127.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ramos: Asia Remains Attractive Market Despite Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
said here Tuesday that Asia will remain an attractive global
market and investment destination despite the financial crisis
that has affected many countries in the region.
</P>
<P>
Addressing officials and employees of the Department of Foreign
Affairs, Ramos said this was precisely why the Philippines sought
to promote regional financial cooperation through the Manila
Framework last November.
</P>
<P>
The Manila Framework, a set of recommendations for regional
cooperation to promote financial stability in the international
monetary system with the support of the International Monetary
Fund, was adopted as a core action strategy for the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) and Asia-Pacific Economic
Cooperation (APEC) member economies.
</P>
<P>
Ramos said last year's informal meeting of APEC Leaders in
Vancouver, Canada, brought the regional community even closer
together in managing the problems of currency depreciation and in
harmonizing the members' actions for regional trade liberalization
and economic and technical cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"We of Southeast Asia, in particular, continue to make good
headway in our economic integration through increased intra-ASEAN
trade and ASEAN trading scheme utilizing our own national
currencies, sub-regional growth zones like the East (ASEAN) Growth
Area (EAGA), liberalized arrangement such as the ASEAN Free Trade
Area (AFTA) and the expanded APEC forum," he said.
</P>
<P>
"It is for these reasons that I, as your president and as
ASEAN chair, believe the region, in spite of its on-going
difficulties, will remain stable and eventually regain its growth
momentum in the foreseeable future," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
