<DOCNO> XIE19980127.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gulf Countries Remain Calm in Oil Price Slide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The Gulf oil producers
have shown concern over the continuous oil price slide starting
from the beginning of 1998, but indicated they would not be hurry
to take immediate response for fear of bringing about
counter-productive effects.
</P>
<P>
The average oil prices in the world market fell to under 15
U.S. dollars a barrel last week with a downtrend still being
perspective, wrecking a month-old agreement that raised the
Organization of the Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC)' output
by 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait Oil Minister Issa Mohammed Al-Mazidi Sunday blamed the
falling world oil prices on quota violations by some of its
fellow OPEC members, as well as Asia's economic trouble caused by
a wide-spread financial crisis and Iraq's possible increased oil
exports under an enlarged oil-for-food formula.
</P>
<P>
In last November, OPEC oil ministers decided to raise their
output ceiling for the first three months of 1998 by 2.47 million
barrels per day to 27.5 million. Meanwhile, Russia proposed to
double the volume of the Iraqi-U.N. oil-for-food scheme which
currently allows Iraq to export 2 billion dollars worth of oil
every six months to buy food and medicine.
</P>
<P>
The loss of more than three dollars a barrel in crude prices in
a few weeks has more than offset the increase in Saudi Arabia's
OPEC quota. Saudi Arabia was allowed to produce 8.76 million
barrels per day under the new quota system.
</P>
<P>
As for Kuwait, the average price for its crudes is slightly
below 13 dollars a barrel according to the last deal. But actual
average price in the second half of 1997 was 18 dollars and it
projected oil revenue at 2.55 billion Kuwait Dinars (8.4 billion
dollars) on a production of 2 million barrels per day.
</P>
<P>
But the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) countries have been
avoiding taking any immediate measures to stop the fall of the
world oil prices and refrained from calling for an emergency
meeting of the 12-member OPEC.
</P>
<P>
GCC groups Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, the United Arab Emirates
(UAE), Oman, Bahrain and Qatar.
</P>
<P>
"They believe a hasty response could send the wrong message to
the market which is already very jittery," a Gulf oil analyst told
Xinhua Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Oil Minister Al-Mazidi said Sunday that the situation is not
yet alarming for its finances although the average price for
Kuwait's oil exports has dropped below a budgeted 13 dollars a
barrel.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia indicated last week that it wants to watch market
developments a while longer before deciding even whether it will
support emergency talks.
</P>
<P>
It said it has no intention of providing a lone prop to the oil
market by cutting back production below its new 8.76 million
barrels per day allocation.
</P>
<P>
The UAE has also indicated it will not easily reverse policy.
</P>
<P>
However, the sharp decline in oil prices this month could
force the Gulf oil exporters, especially Saudi Arabia, to put the
brakes on expenditure in 1998. Saudi Arabia carried out a lavish
spending because of high earnings from high oil prices during the
past two years.
</P>
<P>
The Gulf countries called on OPEC members to strictly abide by
the quotas, indicating that without quota violations prices would
be much higher.
</P>
<P>
Reports said OPEC ministers have increased informal contacts
through the current turmoil in oil markets though there is no
prospect of an emergency meeting of the ministers.
</P>
<P>
OPEC oil ministers are due to hold their next scheduled meeting
in Vienna in June. OPEC groups Algeria, Gabon, Indonesia, Iran,
Kuwait, Libya, Nigeria, Qatar, Saudi Arabia, the UAE and
Venezuela. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
