<HEADLINE> Hospital Acquires Hi-tech Facilities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Mulato Hospital, the most
sophisticated one in Uganda, has acquired radiotherapy facilities
for treatment of complicated cancers, "The New Vision" reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Lawrence Kaggwa, the director of the hospital, said the
facilities worth 1.2 million U.S. Dollars were donated by
International Atomic Energy Agency.
</P>
<P>
According to Kigula Mugambe, the head of the Radiotherapy Unit
in the hospital, the facilities will be used to treat cancer of
cervix, throat, mouth, eye and AIDS-related skin cancers.
</P>
<P>
Radiotherapy is a conventional treatment for advanced cancer
cases. The patients are treated with radiation daily for four to
six weeks.
</P>
<P>
Most local cancer patients report for medical help at their
advanced stage, Mugambe said. With radiotherapy, local doctors
can save many lives, he added. The treatment has attracted
patients from as far away as Rwanda, Zaire and southern Sudan.
</P>
<P>
The government-sponsored hospital has acquired other
facilities and more classified staff members in recent five
years. "We can now manage more complicated cases than ever
before, irrespective of the cause," Kagwa said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
