<HEADLINE> Spring Festival Atmosphere In Chinese Cities (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Fireworks have not been banned from China's port city of
Tianjin, so residents will have fireworks this evening, and a
joyous atmosphere for the Spring Festival, China's Lunar New Year.
</P>
<P>
The municipality will set off 5,000 fireworks at midnight in
four public squares and parks, and the government has allowed
1,100 stores to sell fireworks. However, residents buy less
fireworks this year, as they have come to celebrate the festival
in different ways.
</P>
<P>
Many Tianjin residents have decorated their homes with flowers,
a new holiday fashion among young people in major cities across
China.
</P>
<P>
During the Spring Festival, thousands of people will also enjoy
various recreations like sports, films, TV programs, and travel.
</P>
<P>
Fast-Food in Shanghai
</P>
<P>
More people in the municipality of Shanghai have done something
new by ordering fast-food for the most important dinner of the
Year -- the Spring Festival banquet.
</P>
<P>
Many place orders with local restaurants last week, although
some buy prepared dishes from 250 supermarkets in the municipality.
</P>
<P>
The fast-food banquet helps people prepare dinner more easily
and quickly and avoid complicated preparations, and the dishes
come in many shapes and flavors in a wide range, including sea
food, meats, vegetables, fruits, and desserts.
</P>
</TEXT>
