<HEADLINE> Mubarak Meets With Arafat on Washington Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
held talks with Palestinian National Authority President Yasser
Arafat in his palace on Tuesday morning, the Middle East News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The talks came within the context of consultations Egypt plans
to hold with a number of other Arab countries to discuss the
outcome of the meetings U.S. President Bill Clinton had with the
Israeli and Palestinian leaders in Washington last week.
</P>
<P>
During Tuesday's talks, Arafat, who arrived here Monday night,
informed Mubarak of the results of his tour of Arab Maghreb
region, including Mauritania, Morocco, Algeria and Tunisia, on his
way back from Washington.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was later expanded to include PLO Executive
Committee Secretary Mahmoud Abbas (Abu Mazen), Planning and
International Cooperation Minister Nabil Shaath and Arafat's
Information Adviser Nabil Abu Rydainah.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Prime Minister Kamal el-Ganzouri, Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa and Mubarak's political advisor Osama el-Baz also attended
the talks.
</P>
<P>
Arafat also expounded the outcome of his talks on Monday with
British Prime Minister Tony Blair whose country holds the
six-month rotating presidency of the European Union.
</P>
<P>
In London, the Palestinian leader called for holding an
emergency Arab summit to look into the latest developments in the
Arab world, with particular focus on the Palestinian cause, and
map out the next steps that should be taken to confront the
Mideast peace stalemate.
</P>
<P>
His appeal coincided with a statement by the Cairo-based Arab
League that backed any Arab call for holding a new Arab summit on
the grave conditions of the peace process and the failure of
Washington's peace overtures.
</P>
<P>
Upon their arrival at the airport, Shaath told reporters that
they are returning home from Washington "empty-handed."
</P>
<P>
"The Palestinians have implemented their part of all the
agreements (signed with Israel), but Israel destroyed everything
and offered nothing," he added.
</P>
<P>
Arafat has been voicing his frustration with the Washington
talks which he described as a "failure" and urging Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu to fulfill his obligations.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peace talks have deadlocked since last
March when Israel started to build a new settlement in Arab East
Jerusalem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
