<HEADLINE> Nigeria Begins Drive for Non-oil Export </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria launched Monday an
11-member advisory committee on the export processing factories
scheme in a bid to further promote non-oil export, local press
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The scheme will cater for companies given export processing
factories status but are outside the country's export processing
zones, the first to be commissioned soon in the southeast.
</P>
<P>
Such factories will enjoy the same incentives as those located
in the export processing zones.
</P>
<P>
At the inauguration ceremony in the capital Abuja, Minister of
Commerce and Tourism Emmanuel Udugu explained that the scheme was
planned to "encourage industries to source raw materials locally,
create jobs, increase capacity utilization and generate foreign
exchange".
</P>
<P>
According to him, the committee is expected to create
awareness about the operations of the export processing zone
scheme.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated the government's conviction that
"diversification of the national economic base by way of
developing the non-oil export sector is the only viable and less
painful option for our economic recovery and national progress".
</P>
<P>
The government has planned to establish more export processing
zones in different parts of the country to "aggressively pursue"
non-oil exports in "semi-processed or processed form", the
minister said.
</P>
<P>
Oil and gas processing zones will also be established in
Rivers state in the southeast, he added.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria has over the past few years focused on the development
of non-oil sectors in its drive to reduce over-dependence on oil,
the main sources of the nation's foreign exchange and government
revenue.
</P>
<P>
Construction of the first export processing zone in Calabar
started in November 1991 and more than 90 percent of it has been
ready.
</P>
<P>
However, the shortage of investors has delayed the
commissioning of the zone, the minister disclosed early this
month.
</P>
<P>
At present, only two investors, one producing garments and the
other producing wood work, have installed their machines at the
zone.
</P>
<P>
Altogether 16 companies, both local and foreign, have received
the approval to invest in the zone, but they have not come to
start business.
</P>
<P>
Despite the fact, the government has planned to establish more
export processing zones in different parts of the country to
"aggressively pursue" non-oil exports in "semi-processed or
processed form", the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Oil and gas processing zones will also be established in
Rivers state in the southeast, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
