<HEADLINE> Trucks Banned From Bomb-Ravaged City in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Security forces guarding Sri
Lanka's ancient capital of Kandy have banned all trucks from the
city after a truck bomb explosion killed at least 16 people and
damaged the holiest Buddhist shrine of Dalada Maligawa, said news
reaching here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Security in the city has been tight since the bomb rocked Kandy
Sunday morning. No trucks are allowed to enter the city, some 115
kilometers east of Colombo.
</P>
<P>
Rehabilitation work on the damaged Dalada Maligawa (Tooth Relic
Temple) has been under way. About 3,000 workers, together with
troops, have been called in for the reconstruction project, local
radio reports said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, in Colombo, the main opposition United National
Party (UNP) organized a demonstration this morning in protest
against the government's decision to ban the Liberation Tigers of
Tamil Eelam (LTTE).
</P>
<P>
The government announced Monday night that the LTTE was
outlawed with immediate effect.
</P>
<P>
This decision came one day after some LTTE rebels staged the
bomb attack on the temple. The outer wall, entrance and roof of
the temple were damaged in the incident.
</P>
<P>
The International Committee of the Red Cross has condemned the
attack in Kandy. A news release from the ICRC Colombo Office said
Tuesday that the organization strongly condemns this deliberate
attack on civilians and a place of worship.
</P>
<P>
It added that the attack constituted a serious violation of the
rules of international humanitarian law, which forbid
indiscriminate attacks against the civilian population and
cultural monuments and places of worship.  
</P>
</TEXT>
