<HEADLINE> Hong Kong's External Trade Up in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The value of Hong Kong's
total exports increased by 4.2 percent in 1997 over the previous
year, a local government spokesman said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Within the total exports, the value of re-exports rose by 5
percent, while the value of domestic exports decreased by 0.4
percent. The value of imports registered an increase of 5.2
percent for 1997 as a whole.
</P>
<P>
According to the external trade figures released on the same
day by the Census and Statistics Department of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region, the value of Hong Kong's
re-exports, domestic exports and imports all registered
year-on-year increases in December 1997.
</P>
<P>
The value of total exports comprising re-exports and domestic
exports in December rose by 6.7 percent over a year earlier to
124.4 billion HK dollars (16 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Within the total exports, the value of re-exports increased by
7.4 percent to 105.7 billion HK dollars (13.6 billion U.S.
dollars), while the value of domestic exports increased by 2.8
percent to 18.7 billion HK dollars (2.4 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The value of imports rose to 137.8 billion HK dollars (17.7
billion U.S. dollars) in December 1997, or by 4.9 percent up over
a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the latest trade statistics, the spokesman said
that the values of both re-exports and domestic exports showed a
faster year-on-year growth in December 1997 than in the preceding
month.
</P>
<P>
For 1997 as a whole, the value of total exports registered "a
moderate growth." Taking into account the continued easing in
export prices in 1997, total exports were likely to have grown
slightly faster in real terms in 1997 than in 1996, he noted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
