<HEADLINE> HK Residents Travel out for Chinese New Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 27 (Xinhua) -- As the traditional Chinese
Lunar New Year is around the corner, more and more Hong Kong
residents rush out for their holiday travel.
</P>
<P>
Most of the travelers make run for China's inland for family
reunions or visits to their relatives there.
</P>
<P>
Carrying a big bag on his back, Mr. Cheung lined up at the Lo
Wu checkpoint bordering Shenzhen city with his wife and two
children.
</P>
<P>
"The Spring Festival is the most important holiday and the best
opportunity of family reunion for the Chinese people," Cheung
said.
</P>
<P>
"I took my children with me to see their grandparents, uncles,
aunts and cousins in Huiyang, Guangdong Province," Cheung said,
adding "I hope celebrating the traditional Chinese festival in the
hometown can help the children to learn the country well."
</P>
<P>
Cheung is only one of the estimated 1.4 million people to go to
the inland areas through Lo Wu during the Lunar New Year Holiday.
</P>
<P>
The figure represents a 17.6 percent increase over last year,
said M.K. Tang, senior principal immigration officer of the
Immigration Department of the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region (SAR) of China.
</P>
<P>
Tang said that a total of 107 more officers are being deployed
at Lo Wu during the Spring Festival to help quicken the procedures
handled by Hong Kong residents to get to their hometowns in the
inland to celebrate the festival,
</P>
<P>
All the 60 counters at the checkpoint will be opened to ease
the crowding and nearly 14,000 people will get through the
checkpoint each hour, Tang said.
</P>
<P>
In addition to China's inland, many Hong Kong residents plan to
travel to the Southeast Asia or Macao for their holidays.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's Kai Tak international airport, which is to be
closed on July 6 when the new airport at Chek Lap Kok goes into
operation, is shaking up for its busy last spring festival.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 20,000 passengers are expected to get in or out of the
terminal building daily on peak days, a spokesman for the Civil
Aviation Department said.
</P>
<P>
More than 350 extra flights will be operated between January 26
and February 4, according to the latest information from airlines.
The airport will have handle about 465 flights a day, 35 more than
on a normal busy day.  
</P>
</TEXT>
