<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Traffic Accidents Down in Kampala </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Traffic accidents in Kampala
in 1997 numbered at 4,623, some 20 percent down from the figure
of the previous year of 5,566, "The New Vision" reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The total number of fatal accidents in 1997 is 236, comparing
to 272 in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
There were 240 traffic deaths in 1997, among them 143 were
pedestrians, while the corresponding figures in 1996 were 289 and
171. Traffic injuries in the two years were 1,517 and 3,022
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Declining trend of traffic accidents in the city is a result
of intensified attempts by concerned authorities, said Grace
Turyagumawe, the officer-in-charge of traffic in Kampala.
</P>
<P>
Mass media and other agencies launched a massive education
campaign to teach people proper use of the roads to reduce
traffic accidents, and the police in the city stopped some
drivers who did not have valid driving permits and vehicles in
dangerous mechanic conditions, he added.
</P>
<P>
The authorities also will deploy traffic personnel on the
common accident areas and busy areas to minimize traffic
accidents, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Traffic Department's Speed Control Unit has also
strengthened and provided with transport to patrol all the major
roads leading to and from the city, the official said.
</P>
<P>
The total traffic accidents in the country also showed a
declining trend, with 7,670 incidents in the first 11 months in
1997 and 9,135 in 1996, said John Cossy Odomel, the inspector
general of police.
</P>
<P>
Odomel is optimistic on the trend, saying that police will
intensify its efforts to check on incompetent drivers to minimize
road accidents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980127.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weather Forecast for Major Chinese Cities </HEADLINE>
