<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Renewed Communal Clash Kills Eight in Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 27 (Xinhua) -- At least eight people were
feared dead and about 50 seriously injured in a renewed clash
Monday between Ife and Modakeke communities in west Nigeria, the
official newspaper New Nigerian reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The hostilities, which started early Monday morning with
warriors freely using weapons during the attack, was a major
setback in the on-going peace process between the two rival
communities which signed a peace accord last December.
</P>
<P>
The renewed violence was caused by some Ife youths, who
stormed the Oke-Yidi praying ground where the Modakeke Moslem
faithfuls go for prayers and started felling the trees.
</P>
<P>
Reports said it was the claim and counter-claim over the
ownership of the land that degenerated into the bloody clash.
</P>
<P>
The state Police Commissioner, Sunday Aghedo, confirmed the
clash but declined knowledge of any casualties.
</P>
<P>
The renewed violence is at least the fifth round in a series
since the first unrest was triggered off by the relocation of the
Ife-east local government headquarters from Modakeke to Oke-Ogbo
in Ile-Ife last August.
</P>
<P>
The bloody clashes have claimed the lives of more than 100
people, injured over 200 others and caused huge economic losses
as many houses were burnt and other properties damaged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
