<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel's trade surplus with the United States
skyrocketed by 1.4 billion U.S. dollars to 1.8 billion dollars in
1997, local newspaper The Jerusalem Post reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Israeli Central Bureau of Statistics as
saying that Israeli exports to the U.S. rose 14 percent last year
while imports dropped 9 percent.
</P>
<P>
About one-third of Israel's exports are to the U.S.. In 1997
exports grew by 900 million dollars, mostly in chemicals,
pharmaceuticals and electronics.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Some 250 representatives from social security
organizations around the world are convening in Jerusalem this
week to consider ways to maintain welfare systems in the face of
rising costs.
</P>
<P>
The conference is to discuss how to reduce poverty by expanding
benefits for the very poor populations.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Ministers of trade and economy of nearly 12 countries
are expected to attend the inauguration of the 31st Cairo
International Fair, scheduled for March 11-20.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Minister of Trade and Supply Ahmed Gowaili has
extended invitations to these countries, the Middle East News
Agency reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Some 500 companies from 35 countries are expected to take part
in the fair.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak will open the Cairo
International Book Fair on February 5.
</P>
<P>
During the fair, which goes into its 30th year, the president
will meet with a number of intellectuals, writers and literati in
an open dialog on key issues on the domestic, regional and
international arenas, local newspaper reports said.
</P>
<P>
Up to 2,450 publishers representing 79 Arab and other countries
will showcase about 3.7 million books in the fair's
pavilions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
