<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Central Bank Cuts Lending Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of Israel has
decided to cut its key lending rate from February by 0.5
percentage points to 12.9 percent, the bank said in a statement
available here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The scheduled lending rate reduction is the result of reduced
inflation and inflationary expectations, the statement
said. However, it added, that there is still the need for great
care to ensure a continuation of the drop in inflation seen in
1997.
</P>
<P>
Israel's inflation stood at 7 percent last year, the lowest
level in 29 years. The government has set the same rate for 1998.
</P>
<P>
While welcoming the central bank's interest-rate reduction,
Manufactures Association said that it hopes this is only the first
step in the right direction, pointing out that in real terms
interest rates are far lower in leading industrial countries.
</P>
<P>
The success in lowering inflation rate underlined the
importance of the current monetary policy, particularly in light
of the ongoing economic slowdown and rise in joblessness, the
bank's statement said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
