<HEADLINE> S. Africa Exports Pilotless Aircraft to Algeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 27 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's arms
manufacturer Denel has exported remotely piloted aircraft to
Algeria government troops, South African Press Association
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the 20-million Rand (four million U.S. Dollars)
arms deal with Algeria, Denel said earlier that the remotely
piloted aircraft was a non-lethal reconnaissance drone.
</P>
<P>
Dubbed the Seeker, the surveillance device provided target
location and artillery fire support at distances of up to 200 km
from base, Denel said.
</P>
<P>
The arms deal has been confronted with criticism of South
Africa's weapon sales guidelines, the Cease-fire Campaign.
</P>
<P>
The organization said the ongoing civil war in Algeria had
claimed tens of thousands of lives, saying that there could be no
doubt the intended targets of the Algerian army were Islamites.
</P>
<P>
The organization urged South Africa's Conventional Arms
Control Committee to reconsider its approval of the contract.
</P>
