<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-27 08:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan's Supreme Court Annuls Amended Press Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Jordan's Supreme Court of
Justice late Monday evening declared to "provoke the temporary
Press and Publication Law", which was established last May to
crack down on tabloids.
</P>
<P>
The temporary press law was "unconstitutional" and therefore
the court decided to stop its enforcement, according to the
decision by the 10-member court headed by Acting Chief of the
Supreme Court Abdallah Addad.
</P>
<P>
The amendments to the 1993 Press and Publication Law were
introduced by the government as a temporary law on May 17 when the
Parliament was not in session.
</P>
<P>
Such a move is only allowed in a state of urgency, according to
Jordan's constitution. But a state of urgency was not "detected"
last May, the court decision said.
</P>
<P>
Minister of State for Information Affairs Samir Mutawi told
reporters late Monday evening that Jordan, as a democratic
country, respected the judicial authority's decisions.
</P>
<P>
"We are a democratic country. We respect the law and we
respect whatever is decided by our courts," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The amendments to the Press and Publications Law are now
before our new Parliament and we hope that they will be debated in
the very near future and we shall abide by everything that is
decided by the Parliament," he added.
</P>
<P>
A demonstration erupted in Amman and a number of professional
association presidents resigned in May in protest against the
amended law.
</P>
<P>
The controversial law has forced more than a dozen weekly
newspapers to close down as most of them failed to meet the high
financial obligations the amended law imposed on them.
</P>
<P>
The law asked each newspaper to raise its minimum capital from
about 21,000 U.S. dollars to about 424,000 dollars.
</P>
<P>
The government introduced the amendments to crack down on
tabloids' "yellow reporting" -- slinging mud at the royal family,
leaking military secrets and intruding citizens' privacy.
</P>
<P>
The Press and Publication Law was unveiled in 1993, freeing
up the journalists at state-controlled press and allowing for
publication of independent newspapers and magazines, which then
published moderate criticism of the government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980127.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Cities Witness Spring Festival Atmosphere (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The holiday atmosphere prevails
in Chinese cities in advance of the Spring Festival which begins
on January 28.
</P>
<P>
Chongqing Decorated With Red Lanterns
</P>
<P>
Tens of thousands of red lanterns adorn major avenues in the
southwest China city of Chongqing, China's fourth municipality
established last spring.
</P>
<P>
More than 600 high-rises are decorated with laser and neon
lighting, or strings of smaller colored lights; 36 streets are
decorated with lanterns; and 34 streets feature illuminated
advertising billboards.
</P>
<P>
Lantern exhibitions can also be found in the city's urban
districts, with the downtown area featuring a tower of colored
lights reaching a height of 20 meters, the tallest of its kind in
China.
</P>
<P>
Nanjing Sends Holiday Greetings via Internet
</P>
<P>
The Nanjing city government will send New Year's greetings to
more than 200 domestic departments and friends in 20 countries and
regions via the Internet. The messages will thank recipients for
their efforts to promote cooperation in various fields.
</P>
<P>
This will mark the first time that Nanjing, capital of east
China's Jiangsu Province, has employed Internet to convey New
Year's greeting to foreign organizations.
</P>
<P>
More Nanjing residents are also using Internet to convey
festival greetings to family members and friends abroad.
</P>
<P>
Two communications companies will offer free Internet services
during the festival to attract potential customers. Some 50
prospective subscribers have applied for the services.
</P>
<P>
More than 7,000 Nanjing households subscribe to Internet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980127.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Cities Witness Spring Festival Atmosphere (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Guangzhou, Wuhan Citizens Travel Abroad
</P>
<P>
Traveling abroad for the week-long Spring Festival is the vogue
in Guangzhou, south China's Guangdong Province, and in Wuhan,
capital of central China's Hubei Province.
</P>
<P>
Guangzhou travel agencies report that the number of local
residents travelling to Singapore, Malaysia and Thailand doubles
last year's figure.
</P>
<P>
Trips to Southeast Asia were completely booked 10 days
prior to the festival.
</P>
<P>
Travel agencies have booked trips to Southeast Asia for some
1,000 Wuhan residents, double the number for 1996. Business people
account for the bulk of the travellers.
</P>
<P>
One private enterprise rewards more than 200 of its outstanding
employees with trips to Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
Experts attributed to the cheaper price for the increasing
number of travelers abroad in these cities.
</P>
<P>
Hohhot Reports Brisk Flower Sales
</P>
<P>
Some 30 flower shops in Hohhot, capital city of northwest
China's Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region, report brisk sales in
advance of the Spring Festival. The new trend represents the fact
that people living in grasslands areas have altered their approach
to Spring Festival.
</P>
<P>
People formerly presented cakes when visiting relatives or
friends. Now, however, they present gifts of fresh flowers.
</P>
<P>
People pay little attention to the fact that a flower basket
costs 350 yuan (42 US dollars) and a single flower costs around 14
yuan. High prices seem to make no difference on the most important
holiday for Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
Over 20 varieties of fresh flowers were flown to Hohhot from
Guangzhou and Kunming, capital of south China's Yunnan Province.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
