<DOCNO> XIE19980127.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Increased Minimum Income Tax Threshold Urged in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The Zambia Association of
Manufacturers (ZAM) and the Civil Servants Union of Zambia have
called on the government to increase the minimum income tax
threshold, Financial Mail reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The two bodies suggested that all workers earinging 200,000
Kwacha (about 143 U.S. Dollars) or less per month should be
exempted from paying tax and the tax base widened by including
the informal sector.
</P>
<P>
The current threshold is 50,000 Kwacha (about 36 Dollars) per
month while the informal sector has not been taxed despite the
huge potential existing therein.
</P>
<P>
The local weekly newspaper quoted Mark O'donnell and Japhet
Moonde, leaders of the two organizations, as saying in separate
interviews that the government should consider this in the 1998
budget to be presented this week.
</P>
<P>
Moonde urged the government to stop taxing those getting less
than or about 200,000 Kwacha to lessen their burden.
</P>
<P>
In Zambia most workers are informal ones and in 1996 only
469,000 workers worked in the formal sector of the country with a
nine-million population.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand ZAM has also asked the government to scrap
all import duties on imported raw materials if the manufacturing
sector is to help Zambia rejuvenate its industrial base and
increase job opportunities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
