<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Govt to Boost Energy Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government is
planning to undertake several projects to boost national power
production in the next five years, Energy Minister Chrisanthus
Okemo said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The projects would range from hydro-power to fossil fuels and
geothermal power generation, he said when opening a feasibility
study workshop for the proposed Mutonga-Grand Falls hydro
electric power project on the Tana River.
</P>
<P>
Among projects are a 30 megawatt rehabilitation gas-turbine
plant at Kipevu (implementation period 1998/99), a 75 megawatt
medium speed power plant at Kipevu (1999-2000) and a second 75
megawatt medium speed power plant also at Kipevu (1999-2000).
</P>
<P>
The government is also planning to construct a 64 megawatt
geothermal power plant at Olkaria North East by 2001-2002 and a
60 megawatt hydro power plant on river Sondu-Miriu by 2003-2004.
</P>
<P>
All the projects are part of the current 20-year Power
Development Plan to be implemented before 2002 and will produce
550.5 megawatts in total, said Okemo.
</P>
<P>
The whole plan projects the demand for energy at 5.3 billion
kilowatt hours, and at 912 megawatts for peak power in 2000-2001,
rising to 13.8 billion units and to 2,400 megawatts respectively
at the expiry of the plan period in 2016-2017.
</P>
<P>
The minister added that several high energy power transmission
lines will be constructed in the next five years to ensure
efficient delivery of electric power from these power stations to
various demand centers within the eastern African country.
</P>
</TEXT>
