<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Denies Unhealthy Practices by Foreign Banks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine banking system is
"stronger and healthier" as compared to its counterparts in
Thailand, Indonesia and South Korea, and there is no unhealthy
practice by foreign banks in the country, a senior official said
here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued here, Philippine Press Secretary Hector
Villanueva stressed that contrary to rumors, foreign banks
operating in the country have not resorted to unhealthy practices
at the expense of local commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
"Rumors that tend to undermine the operations of local and
foreign banks are simply not true," Villanueva said.
</P>
<P>
But in a statement released by the Presidential Palace last
Saturday, Central Bank Governor Gabriel Singson was cited as
telling President Fidel Ramos that "gossips about the supposed
shaky status of some big local banks have been largely due to the
unfair tactics adopted by some foreign banks wishing to attract
deposits from Filipino citizens into foreign banks."
</P>
<P>
He said the recent rumor that the country's biggest commercial
and universal bank was experiencing massive withdrawals is
"apparently triggered by the attempt of some foreign banks to win
over the depositors of this bank.
</P>
<P>
Singson's statement has aroused strong reactions from both
local and foreign banks in the country.
</P>
<P>
Villanueva said that the central bank is keeping a day-to-day
monitoring of the performance of all banks in the country,
including their actual resources, earnings and withdrawals.
</P>
<P>
He said the necessary safeguards have been instituted to
promptly check any wrong doing by any local or foreign bank in
order to protect the integrity of the banking system.  
</P>
</TEXT>
