<HEADLINE> Speaker Appeals for Peace in Southern Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Speaker of the Philippine
Congress Jose de Venecia has appealed for calm, and sobriety among
Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) and government troops in
Maguindanao, Mindanao, the Southern Philippines, following renewed
hostilities.
</P>
<P>
Speaker de Venecia, the front-running presidential candidate of
the ruling party, said the two sides should exercise "maximum
tolerance" and help ease the tension in the area in preparation
for the scheduled peace meetings on February 4-6.
</P>
<P>
"Let us prepare for peace, not war. If we have to work an extra
mile to achieve lasting peace in Mindanao, let's do it, said de
Venecia, who was the highest-ranking government officials allowed
by the MILF to enter its heavily-fortified Camp Abubakar in
Maguindanao last November.
</P>
<P>
"We should not allow provocation from either side to negate the
achievements already made by both parties in pursuit of peace," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Speaker de Venecia made the appeal here Tuesday after the MILF
rebels and government troops clashed anew in Buldon, Maguindanao,
on Monday night and last week. Their fighting left 10 rebels and a
government army officer dead in the past week.
</P>
<P>
The renewed hostilities have prompted the MILF and the
government troops to file formal protests with the peace panel as
both sides accused each other of violating a July 1997 ceasefire.
</P>
<P>
Also, the MILF leaders threatened to pull out of the peace
negotiations if government troops refuse to withdraw from areas
near Camp Abubakar.
</P>
<P>
But Speaker de Venecia asked the rebels not to boycott the
scheduled peace meetings and leave it to the negotiating panel to
discuss the formal protests lodged by both sides. 
</P>
</TEXT>
