<HEADLINE> Li Peng On Chinese Economic Situation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng said
today that China's financial and economic situation remains
stable, despite the fact that various other countries have been
adversely affected by the financial crisis in Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
Li, speaking at a ceremony on the eve of Spring Festival, said
that China recorded new achievements in reform and opening, as
well as in various other endeavors, during 1997.
</P>
<P>
Li, a member of the standing committee of the Political Bureau
of the Central Committee of the Communist Party of China, pointed
to the fact that the national economy witnessed steady and rapid
growth accompanied by a low inflation rate, with major economic
indices maintaining promising development trends.
</P>
<P>
He also pointed to successive good harvests, and noted that the
country has recorded major progress in efforts to reform state
enterprises, as well as in economic restructuring, the
construction of key projects and expanding foreign economic and
technological exchanges.
</P>
<P>
The premier said China will continue to introduce basic changes
to its economic system and patterns of economic growth, while at
the same time strengthening agriculture as the foundation of the
national economy and accelerating various reforms to the state
enterprise system.
</P>
<P>
Li said greater efforts will be made to restructure the economy
and open wider to the outside world in order to promote sustained,
rapid and healthy economic development.  
