<HEADLINE> Chinese Doctors Improve Esophagus Transplant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Chinese doctors have greatly
increased the success rate of replacing the morbid esophagus with a
segment of colon, doctors in a hospital in Central China's Hubei
Province said here recently.
</P>
<P>
The complication rate of the 268 patients of morbid esophagus
treated by the No. 1 Hospital affiliated to Hubei Medical
University is 21.26 percent and the mortality rate stands at 2.23
percent. Internationally, the rates are 43.73 percent and 11.41
percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
Although doctors usually choose part of the stomach to
substitute the morbid esophagus, experts regard the colon as a
better substitute for medical reasons. However, the complicated
operation and high complication rate impede doctors'
continuous endeavors.
</P>
<P>
Hubei's medical workers have improved the operation technique
to prevent the partly excised colon from being necrotic.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
