<HEADLINE> Project Launched in Zanzibar to Protect Dolphins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Zanzibar's Foundation
Oceania International (FOT) has launched a project to protect the
endangered species of dolphins.
</P>
<P>
A statement released from FOT said the project will be
executed in three stages, Daily News reported today.
</P>
<P>
In the first phase, researchers will study the behaviors of
the dolphins and look at the impact of tourist activities on the
animals mostly found at the Kizimkazi village, in the south of
the Unguja Island. Researchers have begun their work since last
October.
</P>
<P>
Three observation centers, two on the Unguja Island and one on
Pemba Island, will be built during the project's second phase
scheduled to begin from next month.
</P>
<P>
The centers will carry out the research with visual aids,
communication and medical services, under the direction of Dr
Graham Harding from Britain.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that the project's final phase is to
establish a center for the experts who will learn about dolphin
behaviors under strict medical supervision.
</P>
<P>
The project has won support from the Commission for Natural
Resources in Zanzibar.
</P>
<P>
Dolphins and turtles are rare species in Zanzibar which are
shrinking rapidly in number in recent years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
