<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Pakistan to Increase Oil Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan has been trying to
increase oil production to meet the domestic needs and reduce the
import of petroleum products.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics available, the present oil
production can meet only one sixth of the country's requirement
and the rest is met through import.
</P>
<P>
In the early 1990s, Pakistan's local oil production was 70,000
barrels per day, but now it has dropped to 50,000 barrels per day.
</P>
<P>
The decrease in the production is due to natural depletion of
oil fields in the northern region of the country, according to
official sources from the Ministry of Petroleum and Mineral
Development.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, lack of capital resources and non-economic hurdles
especially in tribal areas of the southwestern province of
Baluchistan, which comprises most of sedimentary area, have
resulted in low exploration activities.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan has a considerably large sedimentary basin. In the
country, wells have been drilled on an average of 5.1 wells per
10,000 square kilometers, and well's successful strike ratio
stands at 1:3 as compared to 1:10 elsewhere in the world.
</P>
<P>
Both the density and the success rate show that Pakistan has
significant untapped potential for oil and gas. However, the South
Asian country drilled only 450 wells in the past 50 years.
</P>
<P>
Established in 1961 for petroleum exploration and development,
the Oil and Gas Development Corporation of Pakistan is the largest
explorer and producer of indigenous oil. But its output, which is
now about 21,000 barrels per day, has been declining because no
new wells have been drilled.
</P>
<P>
Stressing the necessity to improve local oil production, the
Pakistani government led by Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif has been
trying to increase oil exploration activities in the country,
which is facing a trade deficit of 3.3 billion U.S. dollars and
has planned to reduce it by about one billion dollars in the
current fiscal year starting from July 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
The government has announced a new petroleum policy last
October which gives much more incentives than before to foreign
companies already engaged or interested in oil exploration in the
country.
</P>
<P>
The country's private sector has also been encouraged to invest
in this field.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, relevant laws have been amended by the
government to provide legal protection to investors, which is
aimed at creating confidence among potential foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
Another major step taken by the government is to lay more
emphasis on the off-shore exploration by extending the sea limits
for exploration purpose from 200 kilometers to 2,000 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the government has decided to launch extensive oil
and gas exploration in Baluchistan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
