<HEADLINE> Jiangsu Province Ranks Second in China in Export Volume </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, January 27 (Xinhua) -- East China's Jiangsu province
now ranks second in the country in export volume, following
Guangdong province in south China.
</P>
<P>
Latest statistics show that the province, for the first time,
exported more than 15.2 billion US dollars worth of products in
1997, up 16 percent over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The province's import and export volume was valued at 23.87
billion US dollars last year, up 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
Jiangsu witnessed a 30-percent increase in export volume in the
past six years. Its position was raised to the third in 1996 from
the fifth in 1991.
</P>
<P>
The local government attributed the achievement to the
supporting policies adopted for export firms. So far, the province
has had more than 500 foreign trading firms and 700 manufacturing
firms with rights to export directly.
</P>
<P>
The stable prices and the dropping of interest rates in China
also provide an easy environment for the firms, said local
government officials.
</P>
<P>
The foreign-funded firms had the lions' share in the
export. The province's state-owned firms completed 10.3 percent of
the 1997 total export while the foreign-funded ones contributed 43
percent.
</P>
<P>
Industrial products now account for 92 percent of the total
export of the province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
