<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Some 300,000 laid-off
workers in Shanghai, China's largest industrial center, found new
jobs in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the city still had some 150,000
unemployed people at the end of last year, accounting for 2.8
percent of the city's working force.
</P>
<P>
A government official said that the city's re-employment
service centers witnessed a big expansion in 1997 and offered
professional training classes to 218,000 laid-off workers, 72
percent of whom had got new jobs.
</P>
<P>
He said that the municipality has also given a strong push to
the building of its labor market which covers over 20 districts
and counties of Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
The official pointed out that Shanghai's re-employment centers
are aimed at providing organized and regular professional
training to the unemployed in an attempt to sharpen their
competitive edge.
</P>
<P>
Zhu Junyi, director of the municipal bureau of labor, said that
it is an urgent task for the municipal government to enlarge the
employment channels to offer more opportunities to laid-off
workers. 
