<DOCNO> XIE19980127.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangxi Scores Notable Agricultural Achievements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Guangxi
Zhuang Autonomous Regions harvested a 1997 grain output of 16.6
million tons, up 500,000 tons on the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The region's meat output jumped by 440,000 tons to end the year
at 3.35 million tons, Guangxi's output of oil-bearing crops hit
550,000 tons, aquatic products stood at 1.9 million tons, and
fruit reached 3.18 million tons.
</P>
<P>
Marked increases were also recorded for sugarcane and
vegetables, with the former growing by 730,000 tons to end at 28
million tons, and the latter reaching 16 million tons, up three
million tons on 1996.
</P>
<P>
The annual per capita net income of the region's farmers stood
at 1,872 yuan (234 US dollars), up 9.92 percent on the previous
year.
</P>
<P>
The regional government has placed priority on the sector in an
attempt to boost agricultural production. Extensive efforts have
also been made to scientifically develop local agriculture.
</P>
<P>
The government will invest 10 million yuan annually between
1997-1999 to establish agricultural technology stations in order
to improve rural facilities, promote production and provide
scientific and technological support.
</P>
<P>
The goal is to promote new farming techniques in line with
local conditions. The region sponsored 76,400 agricultural
technology classes in 1997, with over 10 million farmers receiving
various forms of training. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980127.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia to Rehabilitate Banking System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government
Tuesday announced a comprehensive program to rehabilitate its
banking system aimed at restoring the confidence of depositors and
creditors and re-establishing the soundness of the system.
</P>
<P>
At a news briefing, attended by several cabinet ministers and
representatives from the International Monetary Fund (IMF),
Finance Minister Mar'ie Muhammad said, "from today the government
will stand behind the commercial banks of the country and
guarantee that obligations to depositors and creditors will be
met."
</P>
<P>
Should any bank encounter difficulty in making payment, he
said, Bank Indonesia, the central bank, acting on behalf of the
government, will immediately step in to make sure that these
payment can be made.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Governor of Bank Indonesia Sudradjat Djiwandono said
the government is guaranteeing that the claims of depositors and
creditors of locally incorporated banks, both rupiah and foreign
currency, will be met.
</P>
<P>
"We anticipate that most depositors and creditors will wish to
keep their funds in the Indonesian banks by rolling over maturing
claims, while they will receive payment if they do choose to
withdraw those funds," Sudradjat stressed.
</P>
<P>
Over the past several months, the waves of economic
difficulties have been taking a heavy toll on the baking system in
Indonesia. And as this has occurred, confidence in Indonesia's
banks has begun to wane. The public has been withdrawing their
deposits from the banking system, reducing the amounts that banks
can lend to corporations.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, foreign banks have become increasingly
reluctant to accept Indonesia letters of credit, making it
difficult to the country to obtain vital imports. Even domestic
banks have become reluctant to lend each other.
</P>
<P>
Sudradjat disclosed that Bank Indonesia, in consultation with
the IMF and the World Bank, is developing a comprehensive set of
prudential requirements of a banking system operating with the
guarantee.
</P>
<P>
To implement the program, Finance Minister Mar'ie also
announced the establishment of a new government institution, the
Indonesian Bank Restructuring Agency (IBRA).
</P>
<P>
The IBRA will be charged with the task of bringing commercial
banks back to financial health, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
Whenever Bank Indonesia discovers that a commercial bank is in
financial distress, it will be transferred to the umbrella of the
INRA. The IBRA will then ask the bank's shareholders to prepare
and implement an immediate rehabilitation plan.
</P>
<P>
"If they are not in a position to do so, then IBRA will take
over the task itself, either by restructuring the bank's
operations and finances, or by merging it with other banks," he
noted.
</P>
<P>
In this way, Mar'ie held that bank by bank, IBRA will build
stronger, healthier and more competitive banking system.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980127.0182 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
