<DOCNO> XIE19980127.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Banks' Situation to Improve in 4th Quarter: Banker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The first six months of 1998
will be difficult for all Thai banks because of rising
non-performing loans, according to Bangkok Bank ltd (BBL)
Executive Chairman Chatri Sophonpanich.
</P>
<P>
He said in an interview on Monday with the Nation newspaper
that he believed "the situation will be better in the fourth
quarter" of this year.
</P>
<P>
He added that whether the banks can survive would depend on
their capital fund level.
</P>
<P>
Chatri said that BBL, Thailand's largest commercial bank, has
set aside provisions of 58 billion baht (1.05 billion US dollars)
against non-performing loans, 40 billion baht (727 million
dollars) more than it needed.
</P>
<P>
BBL estimated non-performing loans accounted for around 18-19
percent of its total credit as of last month. Its total credit was
1,010 billion baht last year (21.36 billion dollars at the
exchange rate of the last day of last year).
</P>
<P>
Chatri revealed that his bank will raise its foreign
sharefolding limit from 25 percent to between 40 and 45 percent as
it must seek overseas investors to participate in recapitalization
in line with the government's request for all banks to raise fresh
capital in order to create additional liquidity in the
cash-strapped economy.
</P>
<P>
He said, "we will definitely raise new capital shortly, of
which the first phase will be 20-25 billion baht (363.7 million to
454.5 million dollars) from an estimated total of 30-50 billion
(545.4 million to 909 million dollars). But there is no money at
home now, and we will have to take in foreign investors."
</P>
<P>
Chatri's statement ended speculation in the financial market
about the intention of the country's largest bank to deal with the
country's gravest financial and economic crisis since World War
II.
</P>
<P>
He said the capital increase will make the bank "more
comfortable" and able to increase credit extension to customers
during the tight liquidity environment.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
