<HEADLINE> Fujian Formulates New Economic Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, January 27 (Xinhua) -- East China's Fujian province,
the native home of many overseas Chinese, has formulated a new
plan to reach an economic growth rate of over 11 percent within
the next three years.
</P>
<P>
Fujian's Gross Domestic Product (GDP) will reach 370 billion
yuan (44.58 billion US dollars) by the year 2000, according to
Governor He Guoqiang.
</P>
<P>
The province currently ranks 12th in the nation in terms of
overall economic strength, and holds a seventh place ranking for
per capita GDP.
</P>
<P>
China's resumption of the exercise of its sovereignty over Hong
Kong will provide more opportunities for Fujian to cooperate with
both the new administrative region and Taiwan. New opportunities
for cooperation will be conducive to promoting an economic upsurge.
</P>
<P>
Fujian will fulfill the plan by accelerating the development of
pillar industries, including the high-tech, petrochemical,
electronics, building materials and forestry sectors.
</P>
<P>
The plan calls for the value-added output of related sectors
to contribute 40 percent to the province's 2000 GDP.
</P>
<P>
Governor He said that the opening policy is a key driving force
for economic development, and he noted that the province will open
still wider to the outside world. Priority will be placed on
drawing foreign investment for the agriculture, basic industry and
high-tech sectors, as well as various other pillar industries.
</P>
<P>
Fujian will extend the greatest possible effort to become a
national window for attracting foreign investment, the provincial
governor said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
