<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Attracts 5.3 Billion US Dollar Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Singapore attracted a total
of 8.5 billion Singapore dollars (about 5.3 billion US dollars) in
new investments last year, up some five percent, local newspapers
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Releasing the investment figures, the government Economic
Development Board (EDB) said it was cautiously optimistic about
1998. But it warned that some investments could be affected if
multinational corporations re-evaluate their projects here and
defer their commitments.
</P>
<P>
According to the reports, EDB Chief Philip Yeo said that the
full impact of the financial crisis on investments would only be
known by the second half of this year, when companies had
recalculated their figures.
</P>
<P>
He was also quoted as saying that as some of the international
banks were "pulling back", the EDB would try to secure the support
of local banks and "if necessary, the EDB would share the risk in
providing the working capital over the short term, where the banks
fell short".
</P>
<P>
He said he was holding talks with 33 banks to persuade them to
continue providing funds for the working capital needs of
promising local enterprises facing a credit squeeze.
</P>
<P>
The EDB said local companies were the largest investors last
year, accounting for some 30 percent of the total commitments,
while the largest foreign investor was the United States, followed
by Japan and European countries.
</P>
<P>
As for the EDB's target of attracting ten billion dollars worth
of new investments by 2000, the EDB leader said that given the
current scenario, it was likely to be delayed by two to three
years.
</P>
<P>
Of the total new investments attracted last year, 45 percent
went to the electronics sector, 35 percent for the chemicals
industry, 16 percent for the engineering sector, while the
remaining four percent for general industries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
