<HEADLINE> Economic Gap Expected to Widen in North-South Italy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, January 26 (Xinhua) -- The economic gap between northern
and southern Italy will widen in 1998, the Svimez Research
Institute said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
This year, the gross domestic product in the less developed
south is predicted to grow by 1.6 percent, while the rest of Italy
will increase 2.4 percent, the institute said.
</P>
<P>
The economic growth was one percent in the south in 1997, when
other places in the country grew by 1.2 percent. At the same time,
consumer spending was up 0.9 percent in the south, but one percent
in the central and northern Italy.
</P>
<P>
The institute said lower inflation and interest rates,
continuous improvement of state accounts and the rise of exports
will help the economic growth in the central and northern regions
in Italy in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Employment in the south fell 0.1 percent last year, while the
other parts of Italy remained stable, the research institute
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
