<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oases Emerging Around Deserts in Xinjiang (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The region has also adopted policies to make balance between
water and soil. It has made it clear that no wasteland can
be developed where there is no water sources, and that investors
should plant trees on one-tenth of the reclaimed land in three
years, said an official with the regional land administration.
</P>
<P>
Jiashi and Cele counties in southern Xinjiang have recovered
some farmland eroded by sand, and they were awarded by the UN
Environment Program for their efforts.
</P>
<P>
And in the Taklamakan Desert, known as the "sea of death" in
the Tarim Basin, scientists and oil workers have succeeded in
opening up 40 ha of farmland with lush greenery.
</P>
<P>
Wasteland-turned farmland has made it possible for Xinjiang to
become the country's largest cotton producer and a major grain
production base. Statistics show that the 400,000 ha of reclaimed
farmland provide 500,000 tons of cotton annually, accounting for
about one-fifth of the national total.
</P>
<P>
Some 60 percent of the reclaimed farmland lies in the watershed
of the Tarim River, which runs more than 2,000 km in the region.
Now, the once denudated diversified-leaved poplar trees have
regained vitality, the pace of desertification has slowed down,
and wild camels, swans and black storks have come back to the
river valleys.  
</P>
</TEXT>
