<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Financial Crisis Dampens New Year Celebrations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Chinese new year celebrations,
once lavish and full of enjoyment, are lackluster this year due to
the on-going financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
In the run-up to the festive holidays, many Chinese-Thais
carefully work out their budgets, canceling faraway trips and
scaling down celebrations.
</P>
<P>
Shops which were once crowded with Chinese-Thais are now filled
with close-fisted customers bargaining for delicacies at knowdown
prices.
</P>
<P>
Bangkok's popular China town appears quiet when in previous
years it heaved with crowds. Many vendors seem bored while waiting
for customers.
</P>
<P>
As usual, celebrations are planned on the eve of the Chinese
new year on January 27, but this year's festivities will not be as
splendid as before.
</P>
<P>
"We celebrate the new year with less money but it does not mean
we are in a gloomy mood," said a businessman who runs a shop in
China town.
</P>
<P>
Due to their meager budgets, many Chinese-Thais prefer to stay
at home during the holidays, unlike the past when they usually
traveled faraway with their families.
</P>
<P>
"It is better to take a rest at home when we lack money in our
pockets," said a watch owner Vasana.
</P>
<P>
Laddawal Horboonchin, 48, owner of a Chinese new year
decorations shop, said she used to travel abroad twice a year in
the past, but this year she would only travel to Chiang Mai,
northern Thailand.
</P>
<P>
"It is a small trip compared with those I had in the past," she
said.
</P>
<P>
"Last year the shop was so crowded that we did not have time to
talk, but it's quiet this year," she said.
</P>
<P>
She said this year her income has dropped to half that of last
year. Many items are still in store and some of her big customers,
such as Robinson department stores have canceled orders.
</P>
<P>
Several dozen customers were wandering around in the shop. Some
were carefully selecting commodities. Several people were just
"window-shopping" outside.
</P>
<P>
A customer said he was buying smaller and less decorations
"because of the sluggish economy," he said.
</P>
<P>
Thailand has been hard hit by a financial crisis since last
Summer when the government floated baht's exchange rate with the
dollar. The Chinese-Thai communities were among those that bore
the brunt of the crisis.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980127.0195 </DOCNO>
