<HEADLINE> Hunan Province Uses Foreign Government Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The introduction of loans from
foreign governments has added impetus to improved infrastructure
development, industrial technology, and the urban environment in
central-south China's Hunan Province.
</P>
<P>
Hunan has used over one billion US dollars in government loans
from 13 countries, including Canada, Japan, Austria and the
Netherlands. Proceeds from the loans account for 20 percent of the
total influx of foreign investments in the province.
</P>
<P>
Loans totalling 580 million US dollars were used to build five
power plants with a total installed capacity of over two million
kw. The power stations generate more than 10 billion kwh of
electricity annually and have greatly eased local power shortages.
</P>
<P>
Total loans of 147 million US dollars have been allocated for
technological upgrades to 15 industrial enterprises.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the Japanese government loans of some 100 million US
dollars were earmarked for efforts to harness the Xiangjiang River
and carry out environmental improvements in urban areas.  
</P>
