<DOCNO> XIE19980127.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oases Emerging Around Deserts in Xinjiang (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The northwesternmost region of
China was no more than a great tract of barren land when Sven
Hedin, a Swedish explorer, was touring it early this century.
</P>
<P>
But now, things are another story. Many man-made oases have
appeared around the deserts in the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous
Region of China.
</P>
<P>
Xinjiang covers an area of 1.6 million square kilometers,
approximately half of which is deserts. At the beginning of the
century, Xinjiang was dotted with 500 small oases with a total
area of seven million hectares.
</P>
<P>
During the mid-century, local farmers launched a campaign to
reclaim wasteland to grow crops.
</P>
<P>
However, this random reclamation led to disastrous results, as
it greatly harmed the ecological system. Wind and sand came pretty
often, encroaching upon vast tracts of land.
</P>
<P>
Another round of wasteland reclamation started in the region at
the beginning of the 1990s, when the central government started to
shift its economic development strategy to the central and western
parts of the country. The resources-rich region was therefore put
high on the agenda as a major agricultural base.
</P>
<P>
Over the past eight years, Xinjiang has spent a huge amount of
money on the control of sand. Windbreak shelters have been built
on 700,000 hectares of barren land around the deserts, thus creating
400,000 hectares of farmland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
