<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OPEC Ministers Meet to Handle Oil Price Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, January 26 (Xinhua) -- Some OPEC ministers met here
Monday at an emergency session to seek ways of curbing the plunge
of crude oil prices on the world market.
</P>
<P>
OPEC said Monday it was getting 13.56 U.S. dollars per barrel
for its crude Friday, compared with 18.81 dollars in November and
16.84 dollars in December.
</P>
<P>
The factors for the price fall include quota-busting production
of some OPEC members, the drop of demand in Asia resulting from
the economic crisis and in European market due to the increase of
oil stocks and unusual warm winter, and Iraq's resumption of oil
export.
</P>
<P>
The group meeting Monday includes the ministers from Iran,
Kuwait and Nigeria, who along with the secretary-general, make up
a committee that monitors OPEC's compliance with its agreed
production levels.
</P>
<P>
The committee can make recommendations but lacks the power to
decide on any production cuts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
