<DOCNO> XIE19980127.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Deep Waterway Project Begins Construction in Yangtze River Delta </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 27 (Xinhua) -- China officially begins the
waterway project at the estuary of the Yangtze River Monday in a
bid to turn Shanghai into an international shipping center.
</P>
<P>
The project, co-launched by the Ministry of Communications, the
Shanghai Municipality and Jiangsu Province, aims to provide a
12.5-meter deep channel for Shanghai and other cities along the
Yangtze River, "China Daily" reported.
</P>
<P>
"With such a waterway, big container ships can enter the
estuary and go far into Nanjing," Zhang Hualin, General manager of
the Yangtze Estuary Waterway Construction Co. Ltd, was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The company is set up to oversee the project and manage the
waterway. The project is expected to cost 15.5 billion yuan and
take 10 years to complete.
</P>
<P>
The first phase will spend 3.27 billion yuan, which will come
from the ministry, Shanghai and Jiangsu. When completed in the
year 2000, the waterway will be 8.5 meters deep.
</P>
<P>
The current channel is only seven meters deep and unable to
accommodate 50,000-tonnage container ships. The estuary allows
only 10,000-tonnage ships fully loaded at the moment.
</P>
<P>
Experts said ships carrying 3,000 to 4,000 TEUs need a
12.5-meter-deep channel. So the project is considered important
to the development of the Yangtze River Delta, said Zhang.
</P>
<P>
Currently, containers, grain and ores are first unloaded at
Beilun Port in Ningbo, Zhejiang Province, and then are transported
into Shanghai, and to the cities in Jiangsu by smaller ships.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai now has 50 shipping companies and 100 container routes
to Europe, America and other East Asian countries. And there are
110 berths of 10,000 tonnages along the Yangtze section from
Nanjing to Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
"But the shallow waterway is an obstacle to the port
development," Zhang added.
</P>
<P>
China now has three coastal economic zones around the Bohai
Bay, the Yangtze River Delta and the Pearl River Delta. The
zones, except the Yangtze River Delta, have deep-water ports.
</P>
<P>
Embankments will be built along the waterway and the project
will not change the ecology, Zhang said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980127.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clean Suburbs Appear in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai residents have
witnessed cleaner suburbs since the municipality introduced its
sanitation improvement program in.
</P>
<P>
Songjiang county received national recognition as a clean
county in 1997, with Fengxian and Nanhui counties basically
reaching national standards.
</P>
<P>
Some 54 towns and townships joined 161 villages in fulfilling
sanitary standards set by the municipal government, with said
figures representing 26 percent and 5.5 percent of the respective
totals, according to local officials.
</P>
<P>
The local government allocated 349 million yuan (42 million US
dollars) for related projects during 1997, a four-fold increase on
the previous year. The funds went for the construction of trash
receptacles, sewage disposal systems and the plantation of flower
gardens in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Rural authorities also provided training classes to improve the
hygiene level of farmers, and a number of villages formed
sanitation teams.
</P>
<P>
An additional 130 villages are expected to join the municipal
list of clean villages in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
