<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Sixty percent of workers in
Guangzhou, the capital of south China's Guangdong Province, have
participated in adult education courses in order to adapt
themselves to rapid changes in society.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong, the vanguard of China's reform and opening drive
which was initiated in 1979, continues to lead the country's
interior provinces, municipalities and autonomous regions in
embracing the consequences of nationwide reform.
</P>
<P>
A growing number of workers face either layoffs or unemployment
resulting from adjustments in industrial structures, the influx of
rural workers, and mounting pressure on the labor market.
</P>
<P>
Municipal labor departments have responded by sponsoring
various classes which have provided training for more than 20,000
workers in the 45 year age bracket. "The classes help workers
learn new skills needed to find new jobs," according to a labor
department official.
</P>
<P>
Statistics for the January-October period 1997 show that the
city doubled its allocations to adult education when compared to
the previous year's period. 
</P>
