<HEADLINE> WFP Projects Successful in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, January 27 (Xinhua) -- A project in Xiangxi in
western Hunan province, central China, supported by the United
Nations World Food Program (WFP), has been recently completed.
</P>
<P>
The Xiangxi Tujia and Miao Autonomous Prefecture is one of
China's poorest areas. It has been suffering from grain shortages
for many years.
</P>
<P>
The project, which lasted six years, has increased the local
per-capita grain output by 500 kilograms and the per-capita income
from 250 yuan in 1991 to 950 yuan last year, according to an
official of the Ministry of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
The Wiangxi project is one of the 57 grain-aid projects
started by the WFP since 1979 to help the poor Chinese to increase
their grain output.
</P>
<P>
The WFP has by now offered 750 million U.S. dollars worth of
grain to 20 million poor Chinese in 81 counties, according to
Maurizio Gnocchia, an official of the WFP.
</P>
<P>
A survey in 16 WFP project areas shows that the grain output in
the areas has increased by 150 percent and over 80 percent of
local people have shaken off poverty.
</P>
<P>
The projects have also brought about great improvements of the
local environment, said the official.
</P>
<P>
Gnocchia said that it is promising to cooperate with the
Chinese government in helping more poor people improve their
living conditions.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
