<HEADLINE> Philippines Recalls 207 Envoys to Cut Cost </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government will
recall 207 diplomats and 1,000 overseas employees this year as
part of its austerity program to overcome the current financial
crisis.
</P>
<P>
According to the Manila Times, the Department of Foreign
Affairs made the announcement Monday.
</P>
<P>
The diplomats will be coming home by the end of March, and the
other employees, who make up 40 percent of the total number of the
country's foreign-based staff, would be returning to the home
office within the year, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Foreign Secretary Domingo Siazon as explaining
that the cutback in the number of diplomats and employees was all
part of the department's austerity measures.
</P>
<P>
"I cannot pay them unless you reduce the number of people who
are paid in dollars. Where will I get the money?" he said.
</P>
<P>
President Fidel Ramos issued a directive earlier this month,
ordering a 25-percent budget cut this year to enable the
government to cope with the currency crisis.
</P>
<P>
Siazon said that he has asked the president to exempt his
department from the mandatory cost-reduction scheme.
</P>
<P>
But he said that even if the department would be exempted from
the mandatory cutback, it will still need about 800 million pesos
(20 million U.S. dollars) to finance its operations as the
original budget for the department is inadequate.  
</P>
</TEXT>
