<HEADLINE> IMF Demand for Budget Surplus Impossible: Thai PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Thailand will not be able to
meet the demand by the IMF for a budget surplus equivalent to one
percent of gross domestic product, Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai
has said.
</P>
<P>
A budget surplus for the year to September is a major condition
set by the International Monetary Fund for a rescue package
approved last August to salvage the Thai economy.
</P>
<P>
Under the IMF demand, Thailand should have a budget surplus of
about 69 billion baht (1.3 billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The local press today quoted Chuan as saying that the Thai
government finds it impossible to achieve the target as a revenue
shortfall of more than 100 billion baht (1.85 billion dollars) is
expected.
</P>
<P>
Chuan declined to disclose whether IMF officials had agreed to
ease the requirement in talks last week with Thai Finance Minister
Tarrin Nimmanhaeminda during his visit to Washington.
</P>
<P>
The IMF repeatedly stressed the need for Thailand to adhere to
the condition. So far no relaxation of the tough austerity
condition has been announced.
</P>
<P>
Thailand has already slashed about 182 billion baht (3.4
billion dollars) from its budget but remains about 120 billion
baht (2.2 billion dollars) short of the target, officials said.
</P>
<P>
Chuan said Thailand needs a few more weeks to come up with
measures to raise additional revenue for the government.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980127.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Sends Envoy to Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 26 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
decided on Monday to send his Deputy Foreign Minister, Victor
Posuvalyuk, as his envoy to Iraq, in attempt to negotiate an end
to Iraq's standoff with United Nations weapons inspectors.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made during Yeltsin's meeting with Russian
Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov, Presidential spokesman Sergei
Yastrzhembsky said.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin is "worried by the development of the situation around
Iraq," Yastrzhembsky said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that Russia's stance on a political solution to
Iraq's standoff with U.N. weapons inspectors had not changed, and
noted that any use of force should be approved by the
U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
Posuvalyuk, who has been busily involved in shuttle diplomacy
over the past four years, was scheduled to leave for Iraq later on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The United States and Britain have not ruled out the use of
force against Iraq since Baghdad ousted American weapons
inspectors three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
This far, two U.S. and one British aircraft carriers have been
sent to the Gulf, further intensifying the situation in the Gulf
region.
</P>
<P>
Russia has long-standing ties with Iraq and consistently
opposed the use of force against the Arab nation.
</P>
<P>
It is also an easing of the United Nations economic sanctions
against Iraq imposed in 1990 after Iraq invaded Kuwait. 
</P>
</TEXT>
