<HEADLINE> Chinese Children In SOS Village Celebrate Spring Festival </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANTAI, January 27 (Xinhua) -- An SOS village in the city of
Yantai in east China's Shandong Province held a little festive
get-together to celebrate the Spring Festival which falls on
Tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
SOS villages have been set up in China to provide a home for
orphaned children. This one has 15 young women who serve as
mothers, living with the children in a family to care for them and
share daily events.
</P>
<P>
According to the village head, Zhu Mingji, the orphans do not
feel lonely here because they receive special and tender care from
these women.
</P>
<P>
Jia Jing, a nine-year-old, contributed a performance of Chinese
traditional music for the party, for which he was awarded with the
applause of the 150 children who were listening attentively.
</P>
<P>
Two hundred and five orphans from 48 counties in five provinces
across the country have been brought up in Yantai's SOS Children's
village since it was founded more than 10 years ago. Of these, 50
have moved away from the village, some even going on to become
university students, and others finding jobs elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
One of them, Li Hua, has gone as far as Cambridge University
for his studies.
</P>
<P>
Another, Yu Lan said, "The SOS Children's village is my home
forever. I love it and the love my mother gives to me is
invaluable." She is now a student in the music department of
Yantai Teachers College, so she contributed a performance. Her
"mother", Sun Aili, who is one of ten model citizens in Yantai,
was moved to tears by Yu Lan's lovely singing.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
