<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Steps up Anti-dumping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 27 (Xinhua) -- China has established an
anti-dumping and anti-subsidy office under the State Economic and
Trade Commission(SETC) in a bid to perfect its anti dumping
campaign, today's China Daily reports.
</P>
<P>
The office, in conjunction with related ministries, is
responsible for investigating damages incurred by alleged
dumping. Meanwhile, the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation(Moftec) and the General Administration of Customs(GAC)
are trying to determine the extent of alleged dumping activities.
</P>
<P>
Moftec and SETC, based on the investigations' results, will
make primary and final recommendations in accordance with related
regulations.
</P>
<P>
Establishment of the office is in response to China's
increasing need to fight foreign dumping, which has become
inevitable with the country's opening up to the outside world, the
English-language newspaper points out.
</P>
<P>
On October 16, 1997, nine Chinese newsprint producers submitted
complaints to Moftec on newsprint exporters from the United
States, Canada and the Republic of South Korea.
</P>
<P>
China's first anti-dumping cases, involving newsprint, were
officially initiated on December 10.
</P>
<P>
SETC began its initiative on January 15, issuing anti-dumping
investigation questionnaires to Chinese newsprint producers.
</P>
<P>
Any party related with the anti-dumping case--including
producers of similar products and domestic newsprint
importers--can contact the newly established office for
information, the Daily quoted a SETC release. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980127.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ecuador Forms Commissions for Talks With Peru </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUITO, January 26 (Xinhua) -- The Ecuadoran government has
designated 12 people to form four commissions to negotiate with
Peru over so-called "deep impasses" over the border problem.
</P>
<P>
The commissions were established on the basis of a timetable
agreed upon by Ecuador and Peru in Rio de Janeiro on January 19,
said Ecuadoran Vice Foreign Minister Diego Rivadeneira on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Relations between the two countries have been tense since the
two became enmeshed in a large-scale border conflict in January
1995. Ceasefire was achieved 50 days later through the mediation
of the Rio De Janeiro Protocol countries, and the two countries
have since held talks to try to solve the conflict.
</P>
<P>
The names of the 12 members will be revealed on February
2. Rivadeneira said that each commission will be comprised of
three Ecuadorans, three Peruvians and a number of advisors who
will be experts on commerce, navigation, military matters,
journalism and business.
</P>
<P>
The commissions will start working simultaneously on February
17 in the cities of Santiago, Buenos Aires, Brasilia and
Washington, the vice minister said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
