<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, January 26 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
economic news briefs in the latin American countries over the past
few days.
</P>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA -- Colombia's oil trade balance showed a 1.1
billion U.S. dollar surplus in 1997, said state petroleum company,
Ecopetrol.
</P>
<P>
The positive balance was due to the sale of 85.2 million
barrels of different fuels for 1.5 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Brazil's state oil company, Petrobras, will invest
10 billion dollars over the next four years to exploit petroleum
resources in 185 new areas of the country.
</P>
<P>
Petrobras President Joel Renno said the company produces just
over 1 million barrels of crude oil per day.
</P>
<P>
Petrobras plans to increase daily production to 1.2 million
barrels this year.
</P>
<P>
SAN JOSE -- Costa Rica's tax authorities declined to increase
taxes, at least during the January-May period.
</P>
<P>
Sources reported that the goal is to make tax collections more
efficient by combating tax evasion and corruption.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- The fuel consumed in Brazil reached 1.68 million
barrels per day in 1997, an increase of 8.4 percent over the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
According to the state petroleum company, Petrobras, Brazil's
gasoline consumption was 308,600 barrels per day, up 9.1 percent
over the daily consumption of 282,800 barrels in 1996.
</P>
<P>
MANAGUA -- A free trade agreement will be signed in April
between the Dominican Republic and the Central American nations.
</P>
<P>
The signing of the accord will fulfill the agreement reached
last November in Santo Domingo by the economic ministers of the
Isthmus and the Caribbean country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
