<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0030 GMT, January 27 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey said on Monday that a constructive dialogue
may be the best way to settle disputes between Turkey and Greece.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Foreign Ministry spokesman Necati Utkan said at a
weekly press conference that Turkey has made its views on the
issue very clear on many occasions.
</P>
<P>
This is believed to be in response to the remark made by Greek
Foreign Minister Theodoros Pangalos last week that Greece intends
to bring the case to the International Court of Justice.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
LAGOS -- Liberians are unhappy with the ongoing withdrawal of
the West African Peace-keeping Force (ECOMOG) from their home
country, the ECOMOG chief said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
"They are not happy that we are reducing our troops. They like
Nigerian soldiers," said Maj.-Gen. Timothy Shelpidi, the newly
appointed ECOMOG force commander on his way to Liberia.
</P>
<P>
"We are reducing troops right now. There is not much happening
in Liberia except in Monrovia," he said, quoted by the News Agency
of Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
"Where there is nothing happening, there is no point having
soldiers in that country," he added.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russian Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev and Japanese
Defense Agency First Deputy Director-General Masahiro Akiyama held
talks on bilateral military cooperation here Monday, according to
the Itar-Tass news agency.
</P>
<P>
Their discussion reportedly focused on the implementation of
agreements on the development of Russian-Japanese military
contacts reached by Russian President Boris Yeltsin and Japanese
Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto in Krasnoyarsk, the Siberia city
of Russia, in November 1997.
</P>
<P>
Sergeyev confirmed his invitation to the chairman of Japan's
Joint Chiefs of Staff, Admiral Kazui Natsukawa, to visit Russia in
May this year.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also discussed the security in Northeastern Asia
and confidence-building measures, the report said.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States on Monday warned Iraq that the
diplomatic string was rapidly running out for Iraqi President
Saddam Hussein before any other options would be taken into
consideration to force him into compliance with U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton and his foreign policy advisers on
Saturday reviewed the situation with respect to Iraq and reached
conclusion that under the present circumstances, U.N. weapons
inspectors could not carry out their mission, State Department
spokesman James Rubin told reporters. "This is a very serious
matter."
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials said that with diplomatic options fading,
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright was expected to soon travel
to Europe, and perhaps to the Middle East, consult with U.S.
allies about possible U.S. military action against Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
