<BODY>
<HEADLINE> American Businessmen Press ASEAN to Cut Tariff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The Association of Southeast
Asian Nations (ASEAN) should not use as an excuse the current
crisis to renege on its commitments to bring down tariffs to zero
percent from five percent before 2003, said the head of an
American delegation.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine newspaper Malaya Tuesday quoted Ernest Bower,
president of the U.S.-ASEAN Business Council, as warning that
ASEAN's delay in meeting the deadline will curtail investment
inflow to the region.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan for an ASEAN Free Trade Area (AFTA) before 2003,
members of the group will cut gradually tariff from five percent
to zero by that time.
</P>
<P>
Bower, who is leading a 15-member mission on a week-long visit
to the Philippines, said here Monday that Americans continue to be
bullish about the region and they want the AFTA in place.
</P>
<P>
While the U.S.-ASEAN Business Council still sees ASEAN as an
important market given its potential, Bower said, tariff reduction
is crucial for ASEAN in attracting new investments into its member
countries.
</P>
<P>
"If you delay, it will only be for short-term, narrow
interests. If you delay, dollar will not fall and (ASEAN) will
fall behind. If you delay, you will not create new investments,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Bower said that the council has received reports that some
ASEAN countries are removing an average of 20 to 30 tariff lines
from the inclusion list of products for reduction to the temporary
exclusion list.
</P>
<P>
Bower's delegation is composed of delegates from American
multi-nationals General Motors, For Motors, Federal Express, and
United Parcel Services as part of an ASEAN tour seeking to monitor
the progress of the AFTA.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
