<HEADLINE> "Blue Seal" Population Up in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The "blue seal" population in
Shanghai had reached 1,523 people in 500 families by the end of
1997, as a result of a local policy to attract trained personnel
from other parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai municipal government decided in 1994 that
non-Shanghai natives can apply for "blue seal" residence and
years later they can apply for permanent residence, if they have a
certain amount of investment in Shanghai's Pudong New Area and
bought apartments with a floor space of over 100 sq. m. or have
worked in Shanghai for over three years.
</P>
<P>
The "blue seal" residents can enjoy equal treatment as
the Shanghai natives do in sending children to kindergartens
and schools.
</P>
<P>
Last year alone, 222 families coming from other provinces were
granted with "blue seal" residence.
</P>
<P>
To attract more trained personnel, a "blue seal company" has
been set up in Pudong in a bid to provide related services for
"blue seal" residents.
</P>
<P>
Local economists said that China's household registration
system has, to some extent, fettered the flow of trained
personnel, and Shanghai's "blue seal" policy will continue to help
the city attract more trained personnel and play an active role
in promoting the local economy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
