<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Concerned About Militarization of Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 26 (Xinhua) -- The United States State
Department expressed today its concern about the increasing
militarization of Cyprus on both sides of the cease-fire line.
</P>
<P>
"We urge all parties to avoid taking actions or making
statements that result in increased tensions in the region and
that detract from efforts to achieve a just and lasting peace on
the island," said State Department spokesman James Rubin.
</P>
<P>
Rubin made the remarks when asked about a newly constructed
military base on the divided island to which Turkey has objected.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday Cyprus said that the newly constructed military base
would only be used in the event of a Turkish attack.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations has repeatedly urged the reunification of
Cyprus and the withdrawal of some 30,000 Turkish troops deployed
on the island.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday Turkey said that it would complain to the U.N.
Security Council over the construction of the military base.
</P>
<P>
"We are aware of Turkish statements about putting before the
U.N. Security Council concerns about the completion of this base,"
Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
"As a member of the U.N., Turkey has a right to raise issues of
concern before the United Nations. It's premature for us to
comment, not having seen all the particulars," Rubin added.
</P>
</TEXT>
