<HEADLINE> US to Grant Jordan More Aid in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, January 26 (Xinhua) -- Jordan's Foreign Minister Fayez
Tarawneh said here Monday the U.S. government has decided to grant
Jordan 225 million dollars in aid for the fiscal year of 1999.
</P>
<P>
Upon returning from a two-week visit to the U.S., Taraneh said
he was informed of the decision by U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright on January 17.
</P>
<P>
He said the aid program will be submitted by the U.S.
administration to the Congress early next month for approval.
</P>
<P>
Tarawneh described his meetings with U.S. officials as "very
successful."
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister was leading a high-level delegation on
January 13-26 in the U.S., which included Minister of Planning
Rima Khalaf and Governor of Central Bank of Jordan Zeyad Fareez.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian-U.S. ties were improved dramatically after Jordan
signed a peace treaty with Israel in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Washington increased its economic aid to Jordan to about 110
million dollars in fiscal year 1997, as a sign of support for the
kingdom's role in Middle East peace making. 
</P>
</TEXT>
