<HEADLINE> Dow Up 12.20 in New York Stock Exchange </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 26 (Xinhua) -- The New York Stock Exchange
(NYSE) closed with modest gains today amid reports of a big
computer merger and AT&AMP;T's cost-reduction efforts by cutting
15,000 jobs.
</P>
<P>
According to preliminary figures, the Dow Jones industrial
average gained 12.21 points to 7,712.94.
</P>
<P>
Falling issues outnumbering advances by a 7-6 margin with 1,323
up, 1,563 down and 544 unchanged.
</P>
<P>
A total of 553.91 million shares were traded against 627.31
million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list fell 0.64 to 956.95, and
the NYSE composite index fell 0.40 to 500.28.
</P>
<P>
The Nastaq composite index fell 14.47 to 1,561.46.
</P>
<P>
AT&AMP;T fell sharply as the Dow's biggest decliner after
announcing plans to save 1.6 billion U.S. dollars by cutting at
least 15,000 jobs and freezing executive salaries.
</P>
<P>
Compaq, another major blue-chip, announced that it agreed to
buy Digital for 9.6 billion dollars in the biggest acquisition in
the computer industry.
</P>
<P>
Compaq fell 2-13/16 to 28-15/16, Digital gained 10 to 55-7/16.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE experienced three sessions of losses totaling 172
points till Friday. Dealers said the market mode so far has
reflected investors' uncertainty over the market direction.
</P>
<P>
Asian markets were mostly higher today. Tokyo's Nikkel stock
index rose 1.7 percent, Indonesia's key stock index rose 5
percent, Malaysia's rose 2 percent, South Korea's rose 1.7 percent
and Hong Kong's rose 0.6 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
