<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S.: Time Running out for Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 26 (Xinhua) -- The United States on Monday
warned Iraq that the diplomatic string was rapidly running out for
Iraqi President Saddam Hussein before any other options would be
taken into consideration to force him into compliance with U.N.
resolutions.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton and his foreign policy advisers on
Saturday reviewed the situation with respect to Iraq and reached
conclusion that under the present circumstances, U.N. weapons
inspectors could not carry out their mission, State Department
spokesman James Rubin told reporters. "This is a very serious
matter."
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials said that with diplomatic options fading,
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright was expected to soon travel
to Europe, and perhaps to the Middle East, consult with U.S.
allies about possible U.S. military action against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
They said Albright could leave as early as this week.
</P>
<P>
A trip by Albright would be an important signal that the United
States was moving toward a military option, political analysts
here said.
</P>
<P>
With regard to Russia sending a special envoy to Iraq in an
effort to try to end the current standoff over the weapons
inspections, Rubin said the United States did not object to the
Russian move, but he said the important thing was not a messenger
but a message.
</P>
<P>
"the issue is not who the messenger is. The issue is the
message: compliance, compliance, compliance and no more excuses,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
The White House also said President Clinton was determined to
press for a strong stand against Iraq for its refusal of allowing
weapons inspectors to enter wherever they deem necessary to find
out any weapons of mass destruction program.
</P>
<P>
"We will be discussing with our allies the correct next steps
to take... We have not ruled out military options in this matter,"
White House spokesman Mike McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
He said "all options" remained open to deal with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
McCurry stressed that despite a raging sex scandal on the
president, which many fear could seriously weaken his power and
prestige here and abroad, Clinton was still focusing on the Iraq
issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
