<HEADLINE> US Tour Aimed to Support Palestinians: Jordanian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, January 26 (Xinhua) -- Jordan's Minister of Foreign
Affairs Fayez Tarawneh said here Monday that his 13-day visit to
the United States was aimed mainly to back up the Palestinians in
their pursuit of peace.
</P>
<P>
Upon his return from the visit, he told reporters that he was
instructed by King Hussein to stay in Washington to coordinate
with the Palestinians in their talks with U.S. officials, said
Tarawneh.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister's trip coincided with Palestinian
President Yasser Arafat's visit to Washington which focused on
ways to revive peace talks between the Palestinians and Israel.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. "for the first time" presented "new ideas" to both the
Palestinians and Israel, said Tarawneh, without giving details of
the "new ideas."
</P>
<P>
"We can not fully assess the situation now because the
concerned parties have agreed to hold meetings on pushing forward
the Palestinian-Israeli peace talks," he said.
</P>
<P>
So far there has been no positive response from Israel, but
due time should be given and the U.S. should continue its
mediation to strike a compromise between the two sides, he added.
</P>
<P>
Tarawneh was accompanied to the U.S. by Minister of Planning
Rima Khalaf, Governor of Central Bank of Jordan Zeyad Fareez and
other senior government officials.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian delegation also discussed other issues with
U.S. officials, including the U.S. aid for the kingdom, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
