<HEADLINE> German Wage Increases Slow Down to 40-year Low in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, January 26 (Xinhua) -- Employees in western Germany saw
their wages increase at the lowest rate for the past 40 years in
1997, mainly due to high competition pressure from abroad and a
record high unemployment at home, official data released Monday
showed.
</P>
<P>
According to the Wiesbaden-based German Federal Statistics
Office, the average pay of western Germany's 6.6 million
industrial workers increased by only 1.4 percent on average in
1997.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the monthly income of the country's more than 3.9
million white-collar employees rose just 1.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Taking into account the inflation rate of 1.8 percent for 1997,
Germany's employees earned even less than 1996 on real terms, the
office said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980127.0251 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia, Japan Seek Military Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 26 (Xinhua) -- Russian Defense Minister Igor
Sergeyev and Japanese Defense Agency First Deputy Director-General
Masahiro Akiyama held talks on bilateral military cooperation here
today, according to the Itar-Tass news agency.
</P>
<P>
Their discussion reportedly focused on the implementation of
agreements on the development of Russian-Japanese military
contacts reached by Russian President Boris Yeltsin and Japanese
Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto in Krasnoyarsk, the Siberia city
of Russia, in November 1997.
</P>
<P>
Sergeyev confirmed his invitation to the chairman of Japan's
Joint Chiefs of Staff, Admiral Kazui Natsukawa, to visit Russia in
May this year.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also discussed the security in Northeastern Asia
and confidence-building measures, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, Akiyama held meetings with the Russian Navy
commander, Admiral Vladimir Kuroyedov, and the head of the Russian
Defense Ministry's Main Department of International Military
Cooperation, Leonid Ivashov.
</P>
<P>
Expressing willingness to develop military ties with Japan,
Kuroyedov said, "Russia and Japan favor full-fledged relations in
the military field."
</P>
<P>
He noted that ties between the two countries' navies are
developing well, but could develop better as "both sides are
prepared for that and have enough experience to make more decisive
steps in this area."
</P>
<P>
Focusing on relations of the Russian and Japanese navies, they
agreed that working groups of the two countries' navy headquarters
will meet in March to coordinate and specify contacts between the
two countries' fleets in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Kuroyedov and Akiyama also discussed military security measures
in the Asia-Pacific region including Northeastern Asia. They said
these measures include "a whole set of events which have been
approved by the Main Navy Command."
</P>
<P>
Akiyama arrived in Moscow on a working visit Saturday and will
leave for Khabarovsk to return home on January 29. 
</P>
</TEXT>
