<HEADLINE> Poll: Popularity for Greek PM Drops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, January 26 (Xinhua) -- Greek Prime Minister Costas
Simitis and his ruling Panhellenic Socialist Movement (PASOK)
government had dropped in popularity, according to an opinion poll
published in the Athens daily "Ta Nea" (The News) today.
</P>
<P>
The poll showed that Simitis' popularity now had dropped to
36.4 percent from 59.2 percent in May last year while Costas
Karamanlis, leader of the main opposition party, New
Democracy(ND), also fell in the popularity by obtaining 43.2
percent compared to 54.1 in September last year.
</P>
<P>
The most popular politician in Greece now is the leader of the
Coalition of the Left and Progress, Nikos Constantopoulos, who
enjoys a popularity of 62.3 percent, followed by Dimitris
Tsovolas, leader of the Democratic Social Movement, of 52.2
percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the support for the PASOK government reduced to 15.8
percent from 25.2 percent in August last year while ND's support
increased to 13 percent from 10.0 percent in November last year.
</P>
<P>
The PASOK government said today that the Greek people's
confidence in the ruling party would be renewed at the election
booths, after the completion of its four-year mandate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
