<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arab Countries to Increase Quotas in IMF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 26 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) board of governors will within days vote on a bill to
increase the fund's capital by 45 percent to 212 billion special
drawing rights (SDRs), or 287 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
IMF sources here said the international financial institution's
current funding stands at 146 billion SDRs (about 197 billion
U.S. dollars), the Middle East News Agency reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Over 10 Arab countries, including Egypt, Saudi Arabia, Kuwait
and the United Arab Emirates, had asked for increasing their
quotas in the fund's capital in a bid to stave off any negative
impact on their marketing power.
</P>
<P>
According to the sources, Egypt's share, pending the fund's
approval, would rise from 678 million to 943 million SDRs.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia's share of 5.130 billion SDRs would also be
increased to 6.985 billion SDRs, bringing the kingdom to the sixth
largest SDR beneficiary in the world.
</P>
<P>
A fattened IMF capital is conducive to the fund's ability to
maintain its role in helping solve urgent economic and financial
problems across the globe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
