<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-26 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Military Action Against Israel Not Allowed in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, January 26 (Xinhua) -- King Hussein of Jordan Monday
told visiting Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai that the
kingdom will not allow anyone to stage military actions against
Israel on its soil, Radio Jordan reported.
</P>
<P>
Jordan will not allow any Palestinian military movement,
including the Islamic Resistance Movement (Hamas), to launch
anti-Israeli actions on the kingdom's land, Hussein said during a
meeting with Mordechai, who arrived here Monday evening at the
invitation of the king.
</P>
<P>
Jordan only recognizes the Palestine Liberation Organization
(PLO) as the legal organization of the Palestinians, he added.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli defense minister paid his visit to Jordan after
Washington failed to bridge the gap between the Palestinians and
the Israelis in.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai was scheduled to return home after a three-hour meeting
with the Jordanian king.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, which was attended by Jordanian Crown
Prince Hassan, the king told Mordechai that Israel and the
Palestinians should not be against each other, but instead should
work together to build peace for the future.
</P>
<P>
If peace is not established, there will be more killings and
destruction, Hussein said.
</P>
<P>
He added that new efforts should be pursued to put the peace
process back on track and push it towards the attainment of a
comprehensive and lasting peace in the region.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Mordechai asked Hussein to help Israel put an end
to the activities of Hamas, especially those against Israel.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai is considered to be the only remaining moderate in
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's hardline cabinet after
last month's resignation of Foreign Minister David Levy in protest
against the government's tough budget and peace policies.
</P>
<P>
Jordan has officially rejected the Israeli attempts to involve
the kingdom in outlining Israel's security maps and in final
status negotiations between the Israelis and the Palestinians, but
it is closely following Israeli-Palestinian developments and wants
to ensure that any final status resolutions take into
consideration of Jordan's national and security interests.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peace negotiations have been at a
standstill since Israel began to expand Jewish settlements in
Arab East Jerusalem in March of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Jordan signed a peace treaty with Israel in 1994, becoming the
second and last Arab nation that conceived peace with the Jewish
state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
