<HEADLINE> Reports: Clinton Lawyer Wants Jones Trial Moved up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 26 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill
Clinton's attorney Monday asked a federal judge in Little Rock,
Arkansas, to move up the trial in Paula Jones' sexual harassment
lawsuit, so the public can judge its merit.
</P>
<P>
Robert Bennett filed a five-page motion asking U.S. District
Judge Susan Webber Wright to bring forward the May 27 trial date,
according to news reports.
</P>
<P>
Jones claims in her lawsuit that when Clinton was governor of
Arkansas in 1991 he propositioned her in a Little Rock hotel room.
She said she rejected his advances, and she was denied promotion
as a state clerk.
</P>
<P>
Clinton has denied the allegations, claiming he does not recall
ever meeting Jones
</P>
<P>
Bennett said, "It is important not only to the president but to
the institution of the presidency."
</P>
<P>
Bennett criticized news coverage of the new allegations against
Clinton involving a former White House intern, referring to an
U.S. Supreme Court's decision last year to allow the Jones suit to
proceed while Clinton was in office, although Clinton's lawyers
wanted to delay the trial until the president left office.
</P>
<P>
He said, "The events of the last few days have shown that the
highest court's confidence that this case could proceed without
undue distraction to the nation's business was unfounded."
</P>
<P>
"The president is being tarred in the media; gossip, innuendo,
and hearsay are being passed off as fact. Allegations by unnamed
sources are claimed to be credible," Bennett was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Bennett accused the broadcast media of abandoning "normal
journalistic restraint" in an effort to be first on the air "with
titillating allegations."
</P>
<P>
The public has no way to evaluate the credibility of the
reports, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
