<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank, WHO, SB Launch Elephantiasis Elimination </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 26 (Xinhua) -- To counter the scourge of
lymphatic filariasis (elephantiasis), the World Bank, the
health care company SmithKline Beecham (SB) and the World Health
Organization (WHO) have jointly launched a new program for
elephantiasis elimination.
</P>
<P>
According to a World Bank announcement here today, under the
program, SB will donate its drug albendazole free of charge to
governments and other collaborating organizations working for the
global elimination of the disease.
</P>
<P>
Over 1 billion people in 73 countries are at risk of
contracting elephantiasis, and there are over 120 million people
already affected worldwide. SB will continue donating the drug
until the disease is eliminated and will also contribute program
assistance and health education. The World Bank will support the
partnership on the country-level by incorporating it in specific
components in all HNP projects over the next three years.
</P>
<P>
"This will be one of the largest global disease-elimination
programs ever undertaken," said Mr. James D. Wolfensohn, president
of the World Bank, who is currently on a visit to Africa.
"Lymphatic filariasis not only disables millions, but also causes
massive socio-economic burdens."
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that, because nearly one-fifth of the world's
population across the world is at risk of infection, it will take
some 20 years to eliminate the disease.
</P>
<P>
New research has determined that albendazole, an SB's drug
which has already become a standard treatment worldwide to combat
intestinal parasites, is 99 percent effective against the parasite
that causes lymphatic filariasis when simultaneously administered
with other antiparasitic drugs.
</P>
<P>
The disease, carried by mosquitoes, often leads to
elephantiasis, the disfiguring enlargement of the arms, legs and
genital organs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
