<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-26 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Hopes Clinton Scandal Not Sap Mideast Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 26 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa Monday expressed the hope that the present circumstances
surrounding U.S. President Bill Clinton do not cast shadow on the
Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
"The issue has captivated the interest of the media and
political circles, but we do hope that it does not undermine the
peace process," he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Clinton has been embroiled in a sex scandal with a former White
House intern. Last week he failed to bridge the gaps between the
Palestinians and Israelis during his separate talks with Israeli
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat.
</P>
<P>
"Israeli rejection still stands firm, disappointment continues
and our rejection of the Israeli rejection stands," he added.
</P>
<P>
The stumbling block on the road to peace has been there for
some time due to Israel's policies, he said.
</P>
<P>
"I hope the American administration will continue to play its
role as an honest broker and to deal with both parties
even-handedly without exercising pressure on one of them," he said.
</P>
<P>
Moussa described last week's meetings that Clinton held with
the Palestinian and Israeli leaders in Washington as "very useful."
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. under Clinton administration has placed the matter
into right perspective by talking to both parties on the same
level and in the same manner and by making proposals," he added.
</P>
<P>
"However, until this moment, there are no substantial results,"
said Moussa, warning that the peace process and the roles of peace
partners are rapidly losing its credibility.
</P>
<P>
"Consecutive meetings as an option to the peace process itself
or handshakes and smiles as an alternative to real progress on the
road to peace can not be accepted by world public opinion," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"We can not go on meeting without reaching just solutions but
mere petty results, as Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat said," he
added.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli talks have deadlocked since last March
when Israel began to build a new settlement in Arab East
Jerusalem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
